[CARD] ishmail.fileAddAltPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add Alternatives Container Option
Use the <bold>Add Alternatives Container</bold> option to insert an attachment into your message using one or more alternative formats. This is useful if you are not sure of the capabilities of the mail reader being used by the message recipient. 


For example, you can include a document in ASCII, Enriched Text, and Post Script formats. If the recipient's mail reader can handle displaying Post Script files, this method will be used to show the included document. If the recipient can't handle Post Script, perhaps the mail reader can handle Enriched Text. If so, this method is used to display the included document. If the recipient can't handle Enriched Text, the message will be displayed as ASCII text.


When you use an <bold>Alternatives Container</bold>, only one view of the message will be presented to the recipient, and it will be the one which uses the highest available capability of the recipient's mail reader.


You can control the order of preference for alternative views. The first one you specify is the least desirable (this should be the ASCII version, which all mail readers can handle). The last one you specify is the most desirable.


§

[CARD] ishmail.fileAddCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add Container Option
Use the <bold>Add Container</bold> option to define structure, or hierarchy, for your message. MIME messages can be defined recursively; they can contain components which contain other components, which can be MIME messages themselves.


There are four kinds of containers you can add. They are:


<bold><italic><bold>Mixed</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Select this option to create a <bold>Mixed</bold> container for one or more body parts. There are no rules on what types of body parts may be put in this container form. This is a "generic" container.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Message Digest</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Select this option to create a <bold>Message Digest</bold> container. This type of container is used to contain a group of one or more complete MIME messages (also known as RFC822 messages), for example a group of messages being forwarded to another recipient.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Alternatives</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Select this option to create an <bold>Alternatives</bold> container.This type of container holds groups of two or more body parts that contain equivalent information, using different formatting of access methods. This option is useful if you aren't sure what level of MIME capability the recipient(s) of your message have, if you aren't sure whether they have MIME capability at all, or if you just wish to give them a choice.


In an <bold>Alternatives</bold> container, each body part contains the same information, accessed or formatted differently. The first body part contains the simplest version, typically plain ASCII text. The last body part contains the preferred version.


For example, if you send a message containing Enriched Text, a version of the text with the Enriched Text attributes stripped out should appear at the front of the message. If you send a message containing GIFs, or other types of binary attachments, these cannot be converted to ASCII. However, any explanatory text you type into the message will be visible.


Another way an Alternatives container can be used is to provide alternate access methods to a file. For example, when attaching a file to a message the most desirable way of doing so is as a Local file. However, this is only available to recipients on the same local network. Attaching a file using FTP access is a more universal, yet slower method of attachment. To cover both cases, you could build an Alternatives container and put two file attachments in it, each referring to the same file. The first attachment would be FTP type and the second (preferred) would be Local file type.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  This option gives you explicit control over creating an Alternatives container. However, you will probably find it easier simply to compose a message normally, then click the <bold>Both if necessary</bold> button at the bottom of the composition window. The <italic>both</italic> in this case refers to a message with both plain text alternative and MIME parts. <italic>Ishmail</italic> will automatically build the Alternatives container for you, and put a plain ASCII text version of your message as the first body part.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent><bold><italic><bold>Parallel</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Select this option to create a Parallel container.This type of container holds groups of two or more body parts which are considered related. The recipient of the message should try to "show" the body parts together. For example, an MPEG video clip and an Audio clip could be put in a parallel container. The recipient's mail tool should try to show the video clip while simultaneously playing the audio clip.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  While the idea of a Parallel container is good, in practice it is difficult to implement well. This is because programs external to <italic>Ishmail</italic> are used to show various body parts. In the example of a video clip and an audio clip, the MPEG viewer program usually takes several seconds to start up, while the audio clip can be played immediately. So, even though <italic>Ishmail</italic> could launch both programs simultaneously you will usually hear the audio clip long before you see the video. Mainly for this reason, <italic>Ishmail</italic> doesn't even try to simultaneously show both clips. When using <italic>Ishmail</italic> to read a MIME message with a Parallel container, you must separately select and view the body parts.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent>Containers appear in the Composition window as icons, with a label indicating the container type. The icons flow in-line with the message text, like included or attached files. Double-click on a container icon and a new Composition window is opened, showing its contents. You can create containers within containers.


Click on a container label and press and hold the right button and you get a pop-up menu which lets you do one of the following:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   delete the container


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   set the container type


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   edit the contents of the container (same as double-click action)


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.fileAddDigPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add Message Digest Container Option
Use the <bold>Add Message Digest Container</bold> option to insert one or more complete MIME (RFC 822) messages into your message. The recipient will be able to individually extract and process the inserted messages. This is a good way to forward a group of messages, keeping message structure intact.


§

[CARD] ishmail.fileAddMixPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add Mixed Container Option
Use the <bold>Add Mixed Container</bold> option to define structure for your message. You can build a hierarchy of text and attachments. Note that you may find it easier just to add attachments and let <italic>Ishmail</italic> build the structure of the message automatically. This option gives you more explicit control over message structure if you need it.


§

[CARD] ishmail.fileAddParPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add Parallel Container Option
Use the <bold>Add Parallel Container</bold> option to insert attachments into your message which should be viewed together, or in parallel. This is intended, for example, for sending an MPEG video clip and an audio clip. The recipient should hear the audio as the video clip is played.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Since the commands used to play the audio clip and show the video clip (in the example used here) have different performance characteristics on different systems, it is impossible to guarantee that the recipient will actually hear and see the attachments simultaneously. The <bold>Parallel Container</bold> is a great idea, but in practice it doesn't always work too well.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sigPrefWin.sigPrefixTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add delimiter before signature
Some mail tools always put a line containing two dash (minus sign) characters in front of the signature. The MIME standard does not include this convention, but it doesn't seem to preclude it either. By default, <italic>Ishmail</italic> does not do this but you can have this extra line added by toggling this parameter <fixed>On</fixed>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sigPrefWin.enableSigTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Add signature to outgoing messages
Toggle this parameter <fixed>On</fixed> to cause <italic>Ishmail</italic> to automatically add your signature to every outgoing message.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can override this for an individual message by toggling the <bold>Append Signature</bold> button in the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.otherForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Additional Headers Field
In the <bold><italic>Additional headers</italic></bold> field, enter additional information that you wish to add to the standard message headers. The content of this additional header information should be in conformance with <italic><underline>RFC-822</underline></italic>. Please refer to <italic><underline>RFC-822</underline></italic> for more information about the supported syntax and content of additional header information.


The <bold><italic>Additional</italic></bold> <bold><italic>headers</italic></bold> field scrolls horizontally, as you enter text, to accommodate lengthy entries. You can use the arrow keys to reveal existing text that is beyond the margins. Each header should be on a separate line. 


§

[CARD] ishmail.optCheckAddrTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Address Checking Option
Toggle this option <Fixed>On</Fixed> to cause
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> to check if addresses are valid before sending
