<italic>Ishmail</italic> opens the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window with the alert pattern and associated command in the text fields.


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Make your change(s) in the <bold>Pattern</bold> and <bold>Command</bold> fields. 


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>Click <bold>Apply</bold> or <bold>OK</bold> in the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window to add your changes to the selected icon in the <bold>Alert Pattern List</bold>.


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.alertWin.insertPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Alert - Insert Button
Use the <bold>Insert</bold> button to add and insert to a specific spot in the <bold>Alert Pattern List</bold>. Commands are searched in order, starting from the top of the list. To cause a command to be processed ahead of the existing commands, click on the command in the list then click <bold>Insert</bold>. Specifically:


<indent>1.	<indent>Select an alert in the <bold>Alert Pattern List</bold> and click <bold>Insert</bold>. <italic>Ishmail</italic> opens the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window.


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>In the <bold>Pattern</bold> field, enter a string pattern to appear in the header field of an incoming message.


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>In the <bold>Command</bold> field, enter the command that will be invoked when the string pattern is encountered in a message header. 


</indent></indent><indent>4.	<indent>Click <bold>Apply</bold> or <bold>OK</bold> in the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window to insert your changes before the selected alert in the <bold>Alert Pattern List</bold>.


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.alertWin.addPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Alert - New Button
Click <bold>New</bold> to begin adding an alert command.


New commands are added to the end of the list. The list of commands is searched in order, starting from the top. If you want your new command to be processed ahead of other existing commands, use the <bold>Insert</bold> button instead. To add a new command to the end:


<indent>1.	<indent>Click <bold>New</bold>. Ishmail opens the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window.


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>In the <bold>Pattern</bold> field, enter a string pattern to appear in the header field of an incoming message.


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>In the <bold>Command</bold> field, enter the command that will be invoked when the string pattern is encountered in a message header. 


</indent></indent><indent>4.	<indent>Click <bold>Apply</bold> or <bold>OK</bold> in the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window. The new alert is added to the end of the <bold>Alert Pattern List</bold>.


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.alertWinEntryWin.keyForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Alert - Pattern Field
Use the <bold>Pattern</bold> field to specify the string pattern to appear in the header field of an incoming message. Each pattern must have an associated command.


The pattern is evaluated as a <italic>regular expression</italic>, as defined by the UNIX <fixed>ed</fixed> command.


§

[CARD] ishmail.alertWin.viewDA.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Alert Command List
This is a list of commands and associated search patterns. The patterns in the list are applied to the headers of incoming mail. If a pattern matches the corresponding command is run. More than one pattern can match a single message. The list of patterns and commands is used in order starting from the top of the list.


You can insert a new pattern and command in front of existing ones, add to the end of the list, or delete one or more patterns and commands by pressing <bold>Insert</bold>, <bold>Edit</bold>, or <bold>Delete</bold> respectively.


§

[CARD] ishmail.optAlertPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Alert Commands Option
Choose the <bold>Alerts</bold> option to specify a command that should be run when a certain string pattern appears in the message header of incoming mail messages. 


When you click <bold>Alerts</bold>, <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Alert Commands</bold> window. From the <bold>Alert Commands</bold> window, you can add, insert, edit, and delete string patterns and their associated commands.  


§

[CARD] ishmail.alertWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Alert Commands Window
Alerts are user-specified commands that run when incoming mail arrives. You can use alerts to invoke a specific command when incoming mail contains a certain string pattern in its header. You can specify a different string pattern for each command you define. When mail arrives, the headers are scanned for a match with any of the patterns. When a match is detected the associated command is executed. 


The Alert command can be any executable program. You can specify the program's full path name, or your <bold><italic>$PATH</italic></bold> environment variable is used to find the program. 


You can pass the message headers and/or the message body to the Alert command. If <bold><italic>%m</italic></bold> is added to the command, <italic>Ishmail</italic> will create a file with the entire message contents and replace <bold><italic>%m</italic></bold> with the name of that file.  <bold><italic>%h</italic></bold> will be replaced with the name of a file containing just the message headers.  <bold><italic>%b</italic></bold> will be replaced with the name of a file containing just the message body.  <bold><italic>%%</italic></bold> will be replaced with %. Here is an example command that will display the <bold><italic>Subject:</italic></bold> and <bold><italic>From:</italic></bold> headers in a new message using the <italic>mfyi</italic> command:


<fixed><bold>mfyi -center "`egrep `^(Subject:|From:)' %h`"</bold></fixed>


The <bold>Alert Commands</bold> window shows the list of current string patterns and associated commands in a box containing two text fields --- the <bold>Pattern</bold> name field and the associated <bold>Command</bold> field. If no alerts have been defined, both fields are empty. 


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Each pattern is evaluated as a <italic>regular expression</italic>, as defined by the UNIX <fixed>ed</fixed> command.


</indent></indent></indentright>You use the four buttons to the left of the text fields to:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Add a new alert


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Insert an alert


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Edit an existing alert


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Delete an existing alert


</indent></indent>When you click <bold>New, Insert</bold> or <bold>Edit</bold>, the <bold>Edit Alert Commands</bold> window appears. It contains text fields in which you can create or modify an alert.


§

