[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window
<Italic>Ishmail's</Italic> <Bold>Composition</Bold> window provides an
easy to use interface for composing, replying to, forwarding, or
re-sending messages. You can open the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window
using the <Bold>Compose New</Bold> option, the <Bold>Reply</Bold> option,
or the <Bold>Forward</Bold> option from the <Bold>Message</Bold> menu
in<Italic> Ishmail's</Italic> main window. 


To use multiple <Bold>Composition</Bold> windows simultaneously, simply
open another window (using the <Bold>Compose New</Bold> option). Your
existing composition window will be left unchanged.


The <Bold>Composition</Bold> window contains these elements:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Menu Bar 


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Header Fields


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Composition Area


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Selection buttons

<Indent><Indent><Indent><Indent><Indent><Bold>

</Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent><<>  </Bold>
<Indent><Indent><Indent><Indent>Set Message
type</Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent> (MIME
or plain)

<Indent><Indent><Indent><Bold>

<<></Bold><Indent>   Wrap text</Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent>


<Indent><Indent><Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Append signature


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Create digital signature


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Encrypt the message 


</Indent></Indent></Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Optional Shortcut
Buttons


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Menu
Bar</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


The <Bold>Menu Bar</Bold> contains four menus from which you choose
options that perform various actions in the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window.
To open a menu, click the menu title in the menu bar:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Bold>Message</Bold> 


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Bold>Edit</Bold> 


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Bold>Options</Bold>


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Bold>Help</Bold> 


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Recipient, Subject
Fields</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


The <Bold>Composition</Bold> window contains up to six header fields for
specifying message recipients, message subject, and additional message
headers. Only the <Bold>To:</Bold> field is a mandatory text field. 


To control which headers are shown, how the header fields are organized,
and how many rows are show in each field use the <Bold>Composition
Window Preferences</Bold> dialog.


Header text fields scroll horizontally to accommodate lengthy entries.
Use the arrow keys to scroll existing text that is beyond the margins.
They also can scroll vertically to accommodate multiple lines (except
the <Bold>Subject:</Bold> field, which is always a single line). A
vertical scroll bar appears as necessary if you enter multiple lines in
a field. 


You can press the <Fixed>Tab</Fixed> key or the
<Fixed>Ctrl-Tab</Fixed> key to move the cursor different text fields, or
you can simply click the mouse pointer in each field. Also, you can
press the <Fixed>Return</Fixed> key while in the
<Bold>Subject:</Bold> field, and the cursor will advance to the next
field. In the other header fields, pressing <Fixed>Return</Fixed> adds a
new line to the field.


Note that the <Bold><Italic>Cc</Italic></Bold>,
<Bold><Italic>Bcc</Italic></Bold>, and <Bold><Italic>Additional
headers</Italic></Bold> fields are not normally shown. You can select
which, if any, of these is shown from the <Bold>Options</Bold> pull down
menu.


The header fields and the procedures for entering text in them are
described below:


<Bold><Italic>To:</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Mandatory field. Identifies primary recipients of the message.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Subject:</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Optional field. Identifies the subject matter of the message.


Enter a brief description of the message in this field. 


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Cc:</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Optional field. Identifies secondary recipients of the message. 


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Bcc:</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Optional field. Identifies recipients who will receive
<Italic>blind</Italic> copies of the message. Blind copy recipients
remain unknown to other recipients of the message. 


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Fcc:</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Optional field. Identifies names of one or more folders into
which the message will be copied when sent.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Additional headers:</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Optional field. Provides additional header information for the
recipient(s).


Enter additional headers to be added to the standard message headers in
the outgoing message. The content of this additional header information
should be in conformance with
<Underline><Italic>RFC-822</Italic></Underline>. Please refer to
<Underline><Italic>RFC-822</Italic></Underline> for more information
about the supported syntax and content of additional header information.


By default, this field is not automatically displayed when you open the
Composition window. To display the field, select the <Bold>Show
Additional:</Bold> button in the Composition window
<Bold>Options</Bold> pull-down menu.


</Indent> <Underline><Bold>Address Formats</Bold></Underline>

There are many valid formats for e-mail addresses, which are used in
the<Bold>To:</Bold>, <Bold>Cc:</Bold>, and <Bold>Bcc:</Bold> fields.
Following are three of the most commonly used on the Internet:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Fixed>user@site</Fixed>


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Fixed>user@site (Real
Name)</Fixed>


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   <Fixed>Real Name
<<user@site></Fixed>


</Indent></Indent>In the above example, only the
<Fixed>user@site</Fixed> part is the e-mail address, the rest is
<Italic>comment text</Italic> which makes the address more readable to
humans. You can type addresses with or without the comment text. To save
space in the header fields, <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> strips the comment
text when you are replying to or forwarding a message. (You can override
this behavior with the <Bold>Reply/Forward Options</Bold> dialog).


There are two ways you can put multiple addresses in a single header. 


<Bold><Italic>Multiple addresses on a single line</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>You can type one or more addresses on a single line, separated
by commas. After you fill the header field the text scrolls to the left.
You can use the cursor arrow keys, as well as other editing keys, to
maneuver in the header field. 


If you enter spaces as part of the comment text of an address, you must
enclose the comment text in parenthesis or you must enclose the e-mail
address between less-than and greater-than characters (angle brackets). 


If a comma is part of the comment text, the comment text must be
enclosed in parenthesis.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Multiple address lines</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>You can press the <Fixed>Return</Fixed> (or
<Fixed>Enter</Fixed>) key after an address, and each address appears on
a separate line. A vertical scroll bar is added to the field if you add
more lines than will fit.


If a comma is part of the comment text of an address, the comment text
must be enclosed in parenthesis.


</Indent> <Underline><Bold>Automatic Comma
Insertion</Bold></Underline>

In previous versions of <Italic>Ishmail</Italic>, a comma was inserted
automatically when you typed space between addresses. This eliminated
the need to type commas. Unfortunately, it also made it difficult to
enter addresses with spaces in the comment text. There were some legal
forms of e-mail addresses which could not be used without
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> sticking in extra commas. So, the comma
insertion feature was disabled. If you liked this feature, and weren't
bothered by the problems it caused, you can enable automatic comma
insertion by toggling <Fixed>On</Fixed> the <Bold>Allow spaces to
delimit addresses</Bold> option in the <Bold>Composition Window
Preferences</Bold> dialog.



<Underline><Bold>Using Aliases</Bold></Underline>

You can use aliases for e-mail addresses. These are shorthand forms of
addresses, or names for a group of e-mail addresses (for example, a
mailing list). The <Bold>Aliases Option</Bold> lets you define and
modify aliases.


To use an alias, simply type it into one of the header fields which
accepts e-mail addresses. You can expand aliases (convert them to their
corresponding address or list of addresses) in any header field by
clicking the mouse cursor in the header and typing Ctrl-A.


To see a list of available aliases that can be used in a header, click
the <Fixed><Bold>[...]</Bold></Fixed> button just above and at the right
hand side of the header field. The <Bold>Select Aliases</Bold> window is
opened.


The <Bold>Select Aliases</Bold> window shows you a single list of
aliases combined from one or more sources. The default source of aliases
is your <Fixed>$HOME/.mailrc</Fixed> file. You can also share a
<Fixed>mailrc</Fixed> file with a group of people, and you can also use
aliases from other programs, such as <Italic>elm</Italic>,
<Italic>pine</Italic>, or <Italic>z-mail</Italic>.


In your <Fixed>$HOME/.ishmailrc</Fixed> file you specify the location of
group or other alias files. For example:


<Fixed><Bold>*groupAliasFile:	/opt/ishmail/1.1/lib/mailrc</Bold></Fixed>


<Fixed><Bold>*otherAliasFiles:	$HOME/.addressbook
$HOME/.zmailrc</Bold></Fixed>


The list of aliases has two columns. The <Bold>Alias</Bold> column is on
the left. The <Bold>Address</Bold> column on the right shows the value
the alias will expand to. This can be an e-mail address or a comma
separated list of aliases or e-mail addresses.


To pick an alias from the list, click to highlight it then click the
<Bold>OK</Bold> button or the <Bold>Apply</Bold> button. You can use
drag select, Ctrl-click or Shift-click to pick multiple aliases, which
will all be copied to the header field, separated by commas.


A vertical scroll bar is added to the list if there are more entries
than will fit in the window. A horizontal scroll bar is show across the
bottom of the list if one or more addresses are too wide to fit in the
window. If there are both horizontal and vertical scroll bars a joy
stick is shown in the lower right corner, which can be used to pan the
aliases and addresses list.


If you have many aliases, you may find the search function useful. Type
a value into the <Bold>Search string:</Bold> field and press one of the
<Bold>Find Next</Bold>, <Bold>Find Prev</Bold>, or <Bold>Find
All</Bold> buttons. <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> will look for a
case-insensitive match for the string in both the
<Bold>Address</Bold> and <Bold>Alias</Bold> columns.


Aliases in the list may be sorted alphabetically, or they may appear in
the order they were created. This is controlled by the <Bold>Sort
aliases</Bold> button in the <Bold>Aliases</Bold> window.


If you toggle the <Bold>Use expanded value</Bold> button
<Fixed>On</Fixed>, the value from the <Bold>Address</Bold> column is
copied to the header field. Otherwise the value from the
<Bold>Alias</Bold> column is copied. If the alias is copied, you can
subsequently press Ctrl-A in the header field to expand it to its
corresponding address. <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> expands any aliases not
yet expanded when you send the message.



<Underline><Bold>Using the Folder Carbon Copy (Fcc)
field</Bold></Underline>

The <Bold>Fcc:</Bold> field lets you tell <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> the
names of one or more folders into which the outgoing message should be
automatically copied. You can type one or more path names of folders,
each on a separate line.


If the folder doesn't already exist it is created for you. The type of
the folder (<Italic>Unix</Italic>, <Italic>mh</Italic>, or
<Italic>MMDF</Italic>) is determined by an option you set in the
<Bold>Folder Preferences</Bold> dialog.


You can tell <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> to fill in the name of the folder
automatically. The name can be the same folder each time, or it can vary
based on the e-mail addresses you are using. See the <Bold>Outgoing Mail
Preferences</Bold> dialog for more information.



<Underline><Bold>Selection Buttons</Bold></Underline>

A selection button just below the message composition area enables you
to append a custom signature to an outgoing message. If you toggle this
button <Fixed>On</Fixed>, the contents of your <Italic>signature
file</Italic> is attached to the message prior to delivery. A change to
this button does not remain in effect after you close the
<Bold>Composition</Bold> window. See the <Bold>Signature
Preferences</Bold> dialog if you want to change the default, which is
<Fixed>Off</Fixed>.


Another selection button determines whether text should automatically
wrap when you type past the right margin. If not, a horizontal scroll
bar will be added to the window if one or more lines in the message are
longer than the window is wide. A change to this button does not remain
in effect after you close the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window. See the
<Bold>Composition Window Preferences</Bold> dialog if you want to change
the default, which is <Fixed>Off</Fixed>.


<Underline><Bold>Menu Options

</Bold></Underline>The <Bold>Options</Bold> pull-down menu offers two
groups of choices. The first five menu items cause
<Bold>Preference</Bold> windows to be opened, which let you customize
the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window and related functions.


The second set of menu items effect the message you are currently
composing. 


<Indent><IndentRight><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP:</X-Color><Indent> These changes only effect the current message. To cause the changes to
stay in effect for subsequent messages, use the  appropriate
<Bold>Preferences</Bold> window.

</IndentRight></IndentRight></Indent></Indent>

You can temporarily show, or hide, various headers fields, such as the:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold> <Bold> Cc: </Bold>field


<Bold><<></Bold> <Bold> Bcc:</Bold> field


<Bold><<></Bold> <Bold> Fcc:</Bold> field


<Bold><<>  Additional headers: </Bold>field

</Indent>


The next menu item, <Bold>Check addresses</Bold>, will cause
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> to request that the
<Italic>sendmail</Italic> program validate the address(es) you typed
into the <Bold>To:</Bold>, <Bold>Cc:</Bold>, or <Bold>Bcc:</Bold> fields.


Next, there are sub-menu which let you control the <Bold>Message
Type</Bold> and <Bold>Message Text</Bold> type.


The <Bold>Message Type</Bold> sub-menu lets you control whether your
message is sent as a MIME message. There are three options:


<Bold><Italic>Plain</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>The message is sent with all MIME formatting and non-ASCII data
stripped from it. This is the ultimate in backward compatibility though,
of course, you loose all the advanced MIME features.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>green</Param><Bold>TIP:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  This is a good choice for the default option, since messages will be
sent in backward-compatible format. If you add something to your
message, such as a formatting change or an attachment, which requires
MIME capability <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> will offer you the chance to
change to the <Bold>MIME</Bold> option before the message is sent.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent></Indent><Bold><Italic>MIME</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>The message is formatted and sent as a MIME message, even if it
contains only plain ASCII text.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Both</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>The message is formatted and sent as a MIME message, and a
<Italic>plain text alternative</Italic> is included in front. The plain
text alternative is the message text with all MIME attributes stripped,
like the <Bold>Plain</Bold> option. Recipients without MIME-capability
will see the plain text alternative, and can ignore the following copy
of the message with encoded MIME data. MIME-capable mail tools will
automatically skip the plain text alternative part and utilize the MIME
encoded data. So, this is the best of both, allowing maximum backward
compatibility while not loosing MIME capability. However, the message
can be much larger, up to double the size, due to the duplicate copies
of the message in different formats.


<IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> <Indent>A
change to this button does not remain in effect after you close the
<Bold>Composition</Bold> window. See the <Bold>Outgoing Mail
Preferences</Bold> dialog for more information about this option or if
you want to change the default.

</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>

The final menu item is the <Bold>Text Type</Bold> sub-menu. It offers
two choices, <Bold>Plain</Bold> and <Bold>Enriched</Bold>. This
selection has no effect on a non-MIME message. The text portion of MIME
messages can be either <Italic>plain ASCII text</Italic> or <Italic>MIME
Enriched Text</Italic>, which lets you apply formatting attributes such
as different <Fixed>fonts</Fixed>, <Bold>bold</Bold>,
<Italic>italic</Italic>, <Underline>underline</Underline>,
<X-Color><Param>magenta</Param>color</X-Color>, and more.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP:</X-Color>
<Indent>Not all MIME-capable mail tools do a good job of handling
Enriched Text. Therefore, the default setting is <Bold>Plain</Bold>.

</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>

<Underline><Bold>Default Shortcut Buttons</Bold></Underline>

If you choose, you can configure a number of shortcut buttons to be
displayed along the top, bottom or sides of the Composition window.
These buttons help streamline your use of the window. There are more
than 50 possible menu functions in the Composition window menu bar that
can be performed by shortcut buttons. 


By default, 12 shortcut buttons are initially displayed in two rows at
the bottom of the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window. 


See <Bold>Buttons Option</Bold> for information on changing the default
shortcut buttons or configuring other shortcut buttons.



<Underline><Bigger><Bold>Composition Area</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


The message compose field is a multiple-line text field in which you
enter the text of your mail message. Click inside the message compose
field to enter the text of your message. This area uses enhanced
<Italic>Motif</Italic> text editing functions in all text fields,
including the message compose field. The editor operates in insert mode.
That is, new text is always inserted to the left of the cursor,
expanding the text field and any existing text to the right.


Here are the essential functions of <Italic>Ishmail's</Italic> text
editor:



<Underline><Bold>Entering Text</Bold></Underline>

<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   To enter text in a blank text field,
click the pointer at the beginning of the field to activate the cursor,
then start typing.


The field expands to the right as you enter text. If you have
text-wrapping set to <Bold>ON</Bold>, the text wraps as you reach the
right margin. However, you can use the Return key at the end of each
line to limit line width if you like.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   To enter new text into an existing
line of text, click the pointer at the desired location (or use the
arrow keys to position the cursor) and start typing. Text to the right
of the cursor is pushed to the right as you type.


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bold>Scrolling Text</Bold></Underline>

To scroll through existing text:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press the Up arrow or Down arrow keys
to scroll up or down a line at a time.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press Control-Up arrow or
Control-Down arrow to scroll up or down a paragraph at a time.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press Left arrow or Right arrow to
scroll left or right a character at a time.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press Control-Right arrow to scroll
a single word and space to the right.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press Control-Left arrow to scroll a
space and a word to the left.


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bold>Deleting text</Bold></Underline>

The Back Space key and the Delete key perform similar functions:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press the Back Space key to delete
text to the left of the cursor a character at a time.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Press the Delete key to delete text
to the right of the cursor a character at a time.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If you want the Delete key to behave like the Back Space key, you can
specify this in the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window
<Bold>Preferences</Bold> window.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent></Indent></Indent>You can also select
(highlight) text, then delete it, as described below.



<Underline><Bold>Selecting Text</Bold></Underline>

There are several ways to select text. Selected text is highlighted to
indicate the range of the selection. You can perform a number of
different functions on selected text, including cut, copy, and paste
functions. 



<Underline><Bold>Selecting Text with the Mouse</Bold></Underline>

<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Drag-select the character(s),
word(s), or line(s) you want to select. 


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Double-click a word to select it. 


You can expand the selection horizontally a word at a time by holding
the left mouse button down on the second click, then moving the mouse
pointer in the direction that you want the selection to expand.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Triple-click anywhere on a line to
select a line. (A line is defined as the text between the beginning of
the line and the next carriage return character.)


You can expand your selection by holding the left mouse button down on
the third click, then moving the mouse pointer up or down to expand the
selection a line at a time.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Quadruple-click to select all of the
text in the field.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Click, then release, the left mouse
button to place the cursor at the start of your selection. Then
shift-click the left mouse button at your intended selection
destination.


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bold>Selecting Text with the Cursor
Keys</Bold></Underline>

<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Shift-Right arrow or Shift-Left arrow
to highlight text a character at a time to the right or left of the
initial cursor position.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Control-Shift-Right arrow or
Control-Shift-Left arrow to highlight a word (and space) at a time to
the right or left of the initial cursor position.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Shift-Up arrow or Shift-Down arrow
to highlight text a line at a time above or below the initial cursor
position.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Control-Shift-Up arrow or
Control-Shift-Down arrow to highlight a paragraph at a time above or
below the initial cursor position.


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bold>Cutting, Copying, and Pasting
Selected Text</Bold></Underline>

Selected text is automatically copied to either a temporary mouse buffer
storage area or a temporary keyboard buffer storage area depending on
the selection method you use. 


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   To place text into the temporary
mouse buffer area, simply select it using any of the mouse selection
methods described above. The selected text is automatically placed in
the mouse buffer. The text remains in the buffer until you either delete
it or perform another selection function.


Once text has been selected, you can:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Paste the selected text to another
location by positioning the mouse pointer at the new location and
clicking the middle mouse button.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Delete the selected text by pressing
the Delete key or the Back Space key. (This operation removes the text
from the temporary mouse buffer storage area.)


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Type over the selected text. (This
operation also removes the text from the temporary mouse buffer storage
area.)


</Indent></Indent></Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   To place selected
text into the temporary keyboard buffer storage area, you must
explicitly press either the Copy key or the Cut key. Once the text is in
the keyboard buffer, it remains the buffer until you either copy or cut
a different text selection into the buffer.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Once you have placed selected text
into the keyboard buffer storage, you can paste it to another location
by positioning the cursor at the desired location and pressing the Paste
key.


</Indent></Indent>For more information about editing text in the X
Windows environment, see <Underline><Italic>X User's
Guide</Italic></Underline> and <Underline><Italic>OSF/Motif Style
Guide</Italic></Underline>.



<Underline><Bold>Using Drag-and-Drop</Bold></Underline>

Drag-and-drop differs from cut-and-paste in that you can use the mouse
to copy whole objects. For example, you can click on a message from the
message list and, by pressing and holding the middle mouse button as you
move the mouse, you can drag the selected message(s) into the
<Bold>Composition</Bold> window. When you drop the message(s), by
releasing the middle mouse button, they are dropped into the text of
the<Bold>Composition</Bold> window at the spot where the mouse cursor is
located. A message which you put into the Composition window this way
appears as an icon. The operation is similar to using the <Bold>Forward
(encapsulate) ...</Bold> option in the Main Window
<Bold>Message</Bold> menu. You can click on the icon and a separate Edit
window will be opened so you can modify the included message.


You can also use the drag-and-drop function to move attachments around
inside the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window.



<Underline><Bigger><Bold>Adding
Containers</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


You can add containers to your message, which allow you to define
structure, or hierarchy, for your message. MIME messages can be defined
recursively; they can contain components which contain other components,
which can be MIME messages themselves.


There are four kinds of containers you can add. They are:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Mixed


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Message Digest


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Alternative


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Parallel


</Indent></Indent>See the help cards for the <Bold>Add
Container</Bold> option on the <Bold>Message</Bold> menu for more
information.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>green</Param><Bold>TIP:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  To show a help card for a pull down menu option, first tear off the
menu by clicking the dotted line at the top. Then select <Bold>On
Context</Bold> from the <Bold>Help</Bold> menu. This changes the mouse
cursor into a question mark. Position the question mark over a menu
option and click the mouse to see the associated help card.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Adding
Attachments</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


You can attach external data files to your message. This is one of the
most powerful features of a MIME message. The data in the attachments
can be plain text or various kinds of multimedia data. The attachments
can be included into the message or attached to the message with a
pointer. Data included into the message can be represented with an icon
or expanded in-line.


See the help cards for the <Bold>Include/Attach</Bold> option on the
<Bold>Message</Bold> menu for more information.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>green</Param><Bold>TIP:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  To show a help card for a pull down menu option, first tear off the
menu by clicking the dotted line at the top. Then select <Bold>On
Context</Bold> from the <Bold>Help</Bold> menu. This changes the mouse
cursor into a question mark. Position the question mark over a menu
option and click the mouse to see the associated help card.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Alternate
Editor</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


You can specify an alternate editor with which to compose text. When you
exit from the alternate editor, your text is then placed in the message
compose field. See the <Bold>Composition Window Preferences</Bold> dialog
for information about specifying an alternate editor of your choice.


To use the alternate editor, click the <Bold>Editor</Bold> button or
select <Bold>Editor</Bold> from the <Bold>Message</Bold> pull down menu.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  It is not possible to completely bypass the
<Bold>Composition</Bold> window when using an alternate editor.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If you are editing a message that has more that one text component (as
may be the case with attachments), the component with the focus
(highlighted border) is the one that will be edited.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If you have used functions from the
<Bold>Edit</Bold> menu, such as changing font style, you will see
<Italic>MIME Enriched Text mark-up tags</Italic> mixed in with the
message text. If you delete these tags you will undo their effect on the
text. You can manually add tags if you like, though you will likely find
doing so in the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window is much easier.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>yellow</Param><Bold>CAUTION:</Bold></X-Color><Indent> If you have set the
<Bold>Message type</Bold> to <Fixed>Plain</Fixed>, enriched text mark-up
tags are stripped from the file before it is sent to the external
editor. You will lose the formatting changes after the external editor
completes.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Spelling
Checker</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


You can use an external spelling checker command to verify the spelling
of your message. The default command used is <Italic>ispell</Italic>.
You can change the default spelling checker command in the <Bold>Composition
Window Preferences</Bold> dialog.


To use the spelling checker, click the <Bold>Spelling</Bold> button or
select <Bold>Spelling</Bold> from the <Bold>Message</Bold> pull down
menu.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If your message contains MIME
<Italic>Enriched Text</Italic>, for example italic, bold, or underlined
text, then <Italic>mark-up tags</Italic> are inserted into the text.
These don't appear in the <Bold>Composition</Bold> window (instead, you
see the effect of the format change) but <Italic>do</Italic> appear in
the text sent to the spell checker command. The
<Italic>ispell</Italic> command will flag most of these as spelling
errors. You can ignore these errors.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>yellow</Param><Bold>CAUTION:</Bold></X-Color><Indent> If you have set the
<Bold>Message type</Bold> to <Fixed>Plain</Fixed>, enriched text mark-up
tags are stripped from the file before it is sent to the spelling
checker. You won't see lots of spurious spelling errors, but you will
lose the formatting changes after the spelling checker completes.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Getting More
Information</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


To get more information about <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> components:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Move the pointer onto the component.
If <Bold>QuickHelp</Bold> is available for the component, a terse
description of the component appears in the message area near the bottom
of the window.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Select <Bold>On Context</Bold> from
the <Bold>Help</Bold> menu. The pointer changes into a question mark.
Move the question mark onto the component, and click.
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> displays a <Bold>Help Card</Bold> containing
concise information about the component and how to use it within the
application.


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bold>Key bindings</Bold></Underline>

There are many shortcut keystrokes recognized by the editor. These
correspond to Motif editor keys or to emacs editor keys. See <Bold>Help
on Keys</Bold> for the complete table of key bindings.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.aliasPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Alias List Button
Click this button to see a list of aliases which have been defined for
e-mail addresses. You can pick one or more aliases from this list to use
in the <Bold>To:</Bold>, <Bold>Cc:</Bold>, or <Bold>Bcc:</Bold> field
(which field depends on which button you click, there is a button to the
upper right of each of these fields).


These aliases may be created by you using the <Bold>Aliases</Bold> window,
from the <Bold>Main</Bold> window <Bold>Options</Bold> menu. Or, you may
create them external to <Italic>Ishmail</Italic>. You can share alias
definitions with other e-mail programs, such as <Italic>elm</Italic>,
<Italic>pine</Italic>, or <Italic>z-mail</Italic>. See the help card for
the <Bold>Select Aliases</Bold> window for more information.


<X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP: </X-Color><Indent>You can use aliases
in expanded or un-expanded form. If you type an alias name and want to
validate that it is defined in your alias list, press the
<Fixed>CTRL-A</Fixed> while the cursor is in the field where the alias
is used. If the alias is valid, it will expand to its full value.


</Indent>
[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.spaceTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Allow spaces to delimit addresses
Some mail tools let you specify multiple addresses just by typing a
space between each. For compatibility, <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> lets you
do this too, if you turn <Fixed>on</Fixed> the <Bold>Allow spaces to
delimit addresses</Bold> button. This feature is also known as
<Italic>automatic comma insertion</Italic>, since that is the effect it
has.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If you allow spaces to delimit addresses you will not be able to enter
addresses containing comment information, since these will fool the
comma insertion logic into thinking you have entered more than one
address. For example:


<Fixed><Bold>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net (Ishmail Support)

</Bold></Fixed>

This address will be incorrectly interpreted, if you have enabled comma
insertion, as three addresses:


<Bold>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net<X-Color><Param>red</Param>,</X-Color>
(Ishmail<X-Color><Param>red</Param>, </X-Color>Support)

</Bold>

</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.deleteTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Delete key behavior
You can control if the Delete key deletes characters from the right of the cursor, or if it works like the Backspace key and deletes to the left of the cursor.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you toggle this option, you must exit and restart <italic>Ishmail</italic> for this change to take effect.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.editCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Edit Menu
Use the <bold>Edit</bold> menu to perform text formatting operations on the current message in the <bold>Composition Window</bold>.


Choose options in the <bold>Edit</bold> menu to emphasize text with various type font and Rich Text formatting attributes such as <bold>bold</bold>, <bold>italic</bold>, and <bold>underline</bold>, <bold>indent</bold>, <bold>left justify</bold> and <bold>right justify</bold>, <bold>subscript</bold> and <bold>superscript</bold>, and so forth.


To use these formatting options, select a text element that you want to format, then click on the <bold>Edit</bold> option of your choice. Ishmail adds the appropriate mark-up language based on <italic><underline>Internet RFC 1341 (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extension)</underline></italic>. 


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.maxFields.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Header Fields per Line
Use these radio buttons to specify how many header fields are shown on a
single line. Putting multiple fields on a line reduces the vertical size
required for the <Bold>Composition</Bold> <Bold>Window</Bold>, but can
make it wider.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.bodyForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Message Area
In the <Bold>Message</Bold> area, compose your mail message. The
standard <Italic>Motif</Italic> text edit widget is the default editor
for <Bold>Message</Bold> area.


You can import data into your message from files or from other mail
messages. The data does not have to be editable ASCII text. ASCII text
or MIME Rich Text can be expanded into your message, as if you had typed
it, or enclosed in an icon. Other types of data are represented by
icons. The data can be included in your message, or attached to your
message with a pointer. For more details, see the
<Bold>Include</Bold> and <Bold>Attach</Bold> options on the
<Bold>Message</Bold> menu.


You can also specify an alternate editor, such as <Fixed>vi</Fixed>,
using the <Bold>Composition Window Preferences</Bold> window..


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>yellow</Param><Bold>CAUTION:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If you choose to use an alternate editor and you are composing a MIME
message with included files, attached files, containers, or Enriched
Text, you need to be familiar with the internal structure of MIME
messages.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.fileCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Message Menu
Use the <bold>Message</bold> menu to perform operations on the current message in the <bold>Composition Window</bold>.


Choose options in the <bold>Message</bold> menu to send your message, to clear or close the <bold>Composition Window</bold>, to include a separate file with your message, to attach a file to your message, and to append a customized signature to your message. You can also select an alternative editor (for example <fixed>vi</fixed>) with which to compose your message. 


§

[CARD] ishmail.optTextTypeCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Message Text Type
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> can create message containing either <Bold>Plain
ASCII text</Bold> or <Bold>MIME Enriched Text</Bold>. Use the sub-menu
to select the message text type.


<X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> <Indent>It is not
necessarily a good idea to create MIME messages containing MIME Enriched
Text, since not all MIME-capable mail tools understand, or handle well,
Enriched Text. Therefore, the text type is not automatically set to
Enriched if you set the message type to MIME.

</Indent>
[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.typeForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Message Type
Since MIME messages ultimately encode all data as plain ASCII text, MIME formatted messages can be read using any mail tool. However, the data format may not be very readable. The <bold>Outgoing mail</bold> type option lets you enhance MIME message readability for people using non-MIME tools. There are three options:


<bold><italic><bold>Plain</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The message is sent with all MIME formatting and non-ASCII data stripped from it. This is the ultimate in backward compatibility though, of course, you loose all the advanced MIME features.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  This is a good choice for the default option, since messages will be sent in backward-compatible format. If you add something to your message, such as a formatting change or an attachment, which requires MIME capability <italic>Ishmail</italic> will offer you the chance to change to the <bold>MIME</bold> option before the message is sent.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent><bold><italic><bold>MIME</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The message is formatted and sent as a MIME message, even if it contains only plain ASCII text.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Both</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The message is formatted and sent as a MIME message, and a <italic>plain text alternative</italic> is included in front. The plain text alternative is the message text with all MIME attributes stripped, like the <bold>Plain</bold> option. Recipients without MIME-capability will see the plain text alternative, and can ignore the following copy of the message with encoded MIME data. MIME-capable mail tools will automatically skip the plain text alternative part and utilize the MIME encoded data. So, this is the best of both, allowing maximum backward compatibility while not loosing MIME capability. However, the message can be much larger, up to double the size, due to the duplicate copies of the message in different formats.


</indent><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can set the default value for this option in the <bold>Mail Preferences</bold> window. (See the <bold>Options</bold> menu).


</indent></indent></indentright>


§

[CARD] ishmail.optMsgTypeCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Message Type
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> can create messages in <Bold>MIME
format</Bold>, in <Bold>plain ASCII text format</Bold>, or
<Bold>both</Bold>. Use the sub-menu to select the message type.


MIME format messages offer the richest features, such as attachments and
formatted text, but not all mail tools understand MIME messages. Users
of mail tools which do not understand MIME will be able to read a MIME
message, but it might not look very nice.


Plain ASCII text messages are the lowest common denominator of Internet
and SMTP mail. If you want to be certain that the recipients of your
message will have no trouble reading it, use this message type.


<X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP:</X-Color> <Indent>The
<Italic>Both</Italic> type option generates a message containing first a
plain ASCII version of your text followed by the MIME version. This
option offers the best of both worlds, though it can double the size of
the message.</Indent>


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.bodyColTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Number of Columns
Specify the number of columns which should be shown in the
<Bold>Composition</Bold> window text area. This determines the width of
the window.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>Yellow</Param><Bold>CAUTION:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  If you have specified a proportional space font, the average character
width is used to determine how wide each column is. Since character
widths can vary greatly in a proportional space font, you may be able to
type many more or fewer characters in the same width.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.headRowTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Number of Rows in Header Fields
You can specify how many rows should be shown for each of the header fields, except the subject line (which is always a single line). When you specify multiple addresses in the <fixed>To:</fixed>, <fixed>Cc:</fixed>, <fixed>Bcc:</fixed>, or <fixed>Fcc:</fixed> fields you can place each address on a separate line. The fields will show a vertical scroll bar if you enter more addresses than there are rows in the field. Similarly, you can enter multiple extra mail headers, placing each on a separate line.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.bodyRowTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Number of Rows in Message Body
Specify the number of rows which should be shown in the <bold>Composition</bold> window text area. A vertical scroll bar will be shown if the message you are composing will not fit in this number of rows.


