§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.showTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Show Extra Fields
You can specify which header fields are shown, or hidden, in the <bold>Composition</bold> window. These fields include:


<bold><italic><fixed>Cc:</fixed> field</italic></bold>

<indent>The <italic>Carbon Copy</italic> field lets you specify people who will receive copies of a message. You can also put multiple addresses in the <fixed>To:</fixed> field. The difference is one of intent. People in the <fixed>To:</fixed> list usually are expected to act upon the message while people in the <fixed>Cc:</fixed> list are usually copied for information only.


</indent><bold><italic><fixed>Bcc:</fixed> field</italic></bold>

<indent>The <italic>Blind Carbon Copy</italic> field lets you specify people who will receive copies of the message, without the people in the <fixed>To:</fixed> list knowing they were copied.


</indent><bold><italic><fixed>Fcc:</fixed> field</italic></bold>

<indent>The <italic>Folder Carbon Copy</italic> field lets you specify one or more mail folders into which the message should be copied when it is sent.


</indent><bold><italic>Other headers</italic></bold>

<indent>This field lets you specify extra mail headers, such as <fixed>Reply-To:</fixed>, which should be added to the message. You are responsible for correctly spelling and formatting all the information in these headers.


</indent>Since each field occupies space in the window, you can minimize the size of the <bold>Composition</bold> window by showing only the fields you need to use. You set the default here, which can be overridden for individual messages.


You can also specify how many header fields are shown on a single line. Putting multiple fields on a line reduces the vertical size required for the <bold>Composition</bold>, but can make it wider.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.optSettingsTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Show Selection Buttons Option
Just below the <bold>Composition</bold> window text area there are several check box buttons and radio buttons. If you have <bold>Option</bold> buttons enabled for display at the bottom (<bold>South</bold>) of the window, the <bold>Selection</bold> buttons will be above the <bold>Options</bold> buttons.


Since the <bold>Selection</bold> buttons cause the window to occupy more vertical space, some people prefer not to see these buttons, especially if they never, or rarely, change the options provided by the buttons.


You can cause the <bold>Selection</bold> buttons to be hidden, causing the <bold>Composition</bold> window to shrink in the vertical direction, by toggling the <bold>Show the Selection buttons</bold> option to <fixed>Off</fixed>.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can override this selection from <bold>Composition Window Preferences</bold> window.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.editorTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Specify Alternate Editor Command
When you use the <bold>Editor</bold> function in the <bold>Composition</bold> window, <italic>Ishmail</italic> starts the editor program you have specified as the <bold>External editor command</bold>. The contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window are passed to the editor, and any changes you make are passed back to the <bold>Composition</bold> window when you exit the editor.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you have applied <italic>Enriched Text</italic> formatting in the <bold>Composition</bold> window, you will see the MIME text mark-up commands mixed in with the text when you use an external editor.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  You cannot completely bypass the <bold>Composition</bold> window, using only an external editor to compose messages. This is because the <bold>Composition</bold> window controls the building of MIME data structures within your message.


</indent></indent></indentright>The <fixed>$FILE</fixed> parameter specifies the name of a temporary file which holds the contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


When specifying commands which don't create their own window, use the <italic>xterm</italic> command to create a window and supply the editor command name as the <fixed>-e</fixed> parameter to <italic>xterm</italic>. Commands, such as <italic>emacs</italic>, which create their own window can be used directly, for example:


<fixed><bold>emacs $FILE</bold></fixed>


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.spellTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Specify Spell Checker Command
You can supply the name of an external command to check your spelling. Similar to the <bold>Editor</bold> function, <italic>Ishmail</italic> starts the spell checker program and passes it the contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window. Changes you make with the spell checker are reflected back to the <bold>Composition</bold> window when you exit the spell checker.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  The default spell checker is the public domain <italic>ispell</italic> command. This is not supplied as part of the <italic>Ishmail</italic> product. If you don't have <italic>ispell</italic>, contact <fixed>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net</fixed> for assistance in getting it.


</indent></indent></indentright>The <fixed>$FILE</fixed> parameter specifies the name of a temporary file which holds the contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


When specifying commands which don't create their own window, use the <italic>xterm</italic> command to create a window and supply the spell checker command name as the <fixed>-e</fixed> parameter to <italic>xterm</italic>.


<fixed><bold>emacs $FILE</bold></fixed>


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.emacsTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Use emacs key bindings
You can set the bindings for short cut keys to mimic either the standard <italic>Motif</italic> edit functions or the <italic>emacs</italic> editor. See the help card for the <bold>Composition</bold> window, or the <bold>Help on Keys</bold>, for a detailed list of the short cut keys.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you change this setting, you must exit and restart Ishmail before the change takes effect.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.wrapTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window - Wrap Text at Right Margin Option
If you select this option, <italic>Ishmail</italic> will insert "soft newlines" into your text as you type past the right margin. The effect is that the cursor will return to the left margin, one row down.


If you resize the Composition Window, your text will automatically re-flow to fit the new margins.


If you press the <bold><italic>Return</italic></bold> (or, <bold><italic>Enter</italic></bold>) key, a "hard newline" is inserted. These will cause the text to break at the same place despite changes to the margins. If you have enabled text wrapping, hard newlines are used to cause paragraph breaks.


If you turn off this option, when you type past the right margin text will scroll to the left. The cursor will not return to the left margin until you press <bold><italic>Return</italic></bold> (or <bold><italic>Enter</italic></bold>).


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you are sending some text in which margins are important, such as columns of text or program source code, turn off text wrapping.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If your message contains plain ASCII text, <italic>Ishmail</italic> "freezes" the line breaks at the time you send the message, by inserting hard newlines. However, if your message contains Rich Text, hard newlines are <italic>not</italic> inserted.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Changing this option in the <bold>Composition</bold> window affects this message. Changing this option in the <bold>Composition Window Preferences</bold> window changes the default behavior for subsequent messages.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Composition Window Preferences
Use the <bold>Composition Window Preferences</bold> window to control the size and format of the <bold>Composition</bold> window, control text wrapping, keystroke bindings, alternate editor command, and spelling checker command.


More explicit help is available for each of the parameters that can be customized. Use the <bold>Help on Context</bold> function. Select <bold>On Context</bold> from the <bold>Help</bold> pull-down menu, then move the cursor over the item of interest and click the mouse.



<bigger><bold><underline>Rows, Columns, and Wrapping Text</underline></bold></bigger>


You can set the number of rows and columns which are shown in the <bold>Composition</bold> window. If the text in the window needs more rows or columns than are available, scroll bars are placed on the text area borders. If you have turned on the <bold>Wrap text at right margin</bold> option, <italic>Ishmail</italic> will reformat the text to fit the window width rather than use a horizontal scroll bar.


Another way to change the size of the window is to click on the outside window border and drag horizontally or vertically. Changes made this way do not stay in effect the next time you run <italic>Ishmail</italic>.


With the <bold>Wrap text at right margin</bold> option, you can control whether <italic>Ishmail</italic> will insert "soft newlines" into your text as you type past the right margin. The effect is that the cursor will return to the left margin, one row down.


You can also specify how many rows should be shown for each of the header fields, except the subject line (which is always a single line). When you specify multiple addresses in the <fixed>To:</fixed>, <fixed>Cc:</fixed>, <fixed>Bcc:</fixed>, or <fixed>Fcc:</fixed> fields you can place each address on a separate line. The fields will show a vertical scroll bar if you enter more addresses than there are rows in the field. Similarly, you can enter multiple extra mail headers, placing each on a separate line.



<bigger><bold><underline>Message Header Fields</underline></bold></bigger>


You can specify which header fields are shown, or hidden, in the <bold>Composition</bold> window. Since each field occupies space in the window, you can minimize the size of the <bold>Composition</bold> window by showing only the fields you need to use. You set the default here, which can be overridden for individual messages.


You can also specify how many header fields are shown on a single line. Putting multiple fields on a line reduces the vertical size required for the <bold>Composition</bold>, but can make it wider.



<bigger><bold><underline>Selection Buttons</underline></bold></bigger>


Just below the <bold>Composition</bold> window text area there are several check box buttons and radio buttons. If you have <bold>Option</bold> buttons enabled for display at the bottom (<bold>South</bold>) of the window, the <bold>Selection</bold> buttons will be above the <bold>Options</bold> buttons.


Since the <bold>Selection</bold> buttons cause the window to occupy more vertical space, some people prefer not to see these buttons, especially if they never, or rarely, change the options provided by the buttons.


You can cause the <bold>Selection</bold> buttons to be hidden, causing the <bold>Composition</bold> window to shrink in the vertical direction, by toggling the <bold>Display the Selection buttons</bold> option to <fixed>Off</fixed>.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can override this selection from the <bold>Options</bold> pull down menu in the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


</indent></indent></indentright>
<bigger><bold><underline>Key Bindings</underline></bold></bigger>


You can set the bindings for short cut keys to mimic either the standard <italic>Motif</italic> edit functions or the <italic>emacs</italic> editor. 


You can also control if the Delete key deletes characters from the right of the cursor, or if it works like the Backspace key and deletes to the left of the cursor.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you toggle either the <bold>Use Emacs key bindings</bold> key or the <bold>Delete key works like Backspace</bold> key, you must exit and restart <italic>Ishmail</italic> for this change to take effect.


