<bigger><bold><underline>Specifying Multiple Addresses</underline></bold></bigger>


When you specify more than one address in the <fixed>To:</fixed>, <fixed>Cc:</fixed>, <fixed>Bcc:</fixed>, or <fixed>Fcc:</fixed> fields you can place each address on a separate line, by pressing the <fixed>Return</fixed> (or <fixed>Enter</fixed>) key after each one.


Or, you can type multiple addresses on a single line, provided that you type a comma between each address.


Some mail tools let you specify multiple addresses just by typing a space between each. For compatibility, <italic>Ishmail</italic> lets you do this too, if you turn <fixed>on</fixed> the <bold>Allow spaces to delimit addresses</bold> button.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you allow spaces to delimit addresses you will not be able to enter addresses containing comment information, since these will fool the comma insertion logic into thinking you have entered more than one address.


</indent></indent></indentright>
<bigger><bold><underline>External Commands - Editor and Spell Checker</underline></bold></bigger>


When you use the <bold>Editor</bold> function in the <bold>Composition</bold> window, <italic>Ishmail</italic> starts the editor program you have specified as the <bold>External editor command</bold>. The contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window are passed to the editor, and any changes you make are passed back to the <bold>Composition</bold> window when you exit the editor.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you have applied <italic>Enriched Text</italic> formatting in the <bold>Composition</bold> window, you will see the MIME text mark-up commands mixed in with the text when you use an external editor.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  You cannot completely bypass the <bold>Composition</bold> window, using only an external editor to compose messages. This is because the <bold>Composition</bold> window controls the building of MIME data structures within your message.


</indent></indent></indentright>You can also supply the name of an external command to check your spelling. Similar to the <bold>Editor</bold> function, <italic>Ishmail</italic> starts the spell checker program and passes it the contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window. Changes you make with the spell checker are reflected back to the <bold>Composition</bold> window when you exit the spell checker.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  The default spell checker is the public domain <italic>ispell</italic> command. This is not supplied as part of the <italic>Ishmail</italic> product. If you don't have <italic>ispell</italic>, contact <fixed>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net</fixed> for assistance in getting it.


</indent></indent></indentright>For either command, the <fixed>$FILE</fixed> parameter specifies the name of a temporary file which holds the contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


When specifying commands which don't create their own window, use the <italic>xterm</italic> command to create a window and supply the spell checker or editor command name as the <fixed>-e</fixed> parameter to <italic>xterm</italic>. Commands, such as <italic>emacs</italic>, which create their own window can be used directly, for example:


<fixed><bold>emacs $FILE</bold></fixed>


§

[CARD] ishmail.confirmWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Confirmation Preferences Window
There are many actions that you can request the <italic>Ishmail</italic> program to do which have irreversible effects, such as permanently deleting a mail folder or clearing the contents of the <bold><italic>Composition Window</italic></bold>. To make <italic>Ishmail</italic> friendly to use, these actions cause a pop up window to be opened which requests that you confirm that you <italic>really</italic> want to do the action.


Experienced users of Ishmail may become annoyed, however, at seeing a confirmation pop up window when their answer to the question <italic>always</italic> is "Yes, I know what I'm doing."


The <bold><italic>Confirmation Preferences</italic></bold> window lets you selectively disable the confirmation pop up window for various actions.


§

[CARD] ishmail.optConfirmPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Confirmations Option
Choose the <bold>Confirmations ...</bold> option to control which actions require explicit confirmation before they are done.


Actions that can be selectively confirmed include:


<bold><italic>Quit and Exit</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to quit (or exit) from <italic>Ishmail</italic>?


</indent><bold><italic>Save changes during exit</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you want to save changes to folders before exit?


</indent><bold><italic>Folder type for new folders</italic></bold>

<indent>Which type (Unix, mh, or MMDF) of folder do you wish to create?


</indent><bold><italic>Folder deletion</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to delete a folder?


</indent><bold><italic>Sending messages with no subject</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to send a message with no subject header?


</indent><bold><italic>Sending messages with an empty body</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to send an empty (null) message?


</indent><bold><italic>Clearing the <bold><italic>Composition Window</italic></bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to lose everything you've typed in the window?


</indent><bold><italic>Closing the <bold><italic>Composition Window</italic></bold> with un-mailed contents</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to abandon this new message?


</indent><bold><italic>Sending a message as plain text even though there will be information lost</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to lose MIME data when this message is sent?


</indent><bold><italic>Mailing text that contains 8-bit characters as plain text</italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to send a message without encoding, even though this means some information may be lost along the way?


</indent><bold><italic>Deleting inclusions or attachments in the <bold><italic>Composition Window</italic></bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Do you really want to delete included data, with no chance for undelete?


</indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.readWin.fileMimePB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Convert Sun mailtool message to MIME format
This option will be selectable if the message you are viewing is a
multi-part message created by Sun's <Italic>mailtool</Italic> program.
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> will attempt to convert the message to MIME
format, so that the multiple message parts can be viewed correctly.


<X-Color><Param>yellow</Param>CAUTION:</X-Color> <Indent>Sun has never
published a specification for the format of <Italic>mailtool</Italic> messages,
so it is not guaranteed that <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> will correctly
identify all possible formats <Italic>mailtool</Italic> can generate.
Also, the <Fixed>Content-Length</Fixed> specification in
<Italic>mailtool</Italic> messages is notoriously inaccurate, which can
lead to incorrect interpretation for the message format.


If the message does not convert correctly, close the folder without
saving changes and the message will be restored to its original format.


</Indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.fileWin.okPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Copy/Move Buttons
Click <bold>Copy</bold> to copy the message from the current folder to the folder you specified in the <bold>Selected</bold> <bold>Folder</bold> field. A copy remains in the current directory.


Click <bold>Move</bold> to move the message from the current folder to the folder you specified in the <bold>Selected</bold> <bold>Folder</bold> field. The message is marked for deletion in the current directory.


§

[CARD] ishmail.dirForm.dirNameTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Current Directory Field
The <bold>Current Directory</bold> field contains the name of the current directory. To change to a different directory, type another directory's name in the <bold>Current Directory</bold> field and press <fixed>Return</fixed> (or <fixed>Enter</fixed>) or click the <bold>Set</bold> button. Or, select a directory name from the list below this field.


§

[CARD] ishmail.readPrefWin.decryptTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Decryption Command
Use this field to name a command which is used to
<Bold>decrypt</Bold> the contents of an encrypted message. 


You may specify a full path name if the command's directory is not in
your search path.


You can also specify parameters for the command. You can use
<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> variables such as
<Bold>%s</Bold>, which represents the contents of the message body.


<X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> The
<Bold><Italic>ishmail</Italic></Bold> package does
<X-Color><Param>red</Param><Bold>not</Bold></X-Color> include the
<Fixed><Bold>pgp</Bold></Fixed> command itself, nor any other encryption
program. U.S. laws restrict distribution of encryption technology. You
must supply your own encryption and decryption software.

§

[CARD] ishmail.defFolderTypeWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Default Folder Type
Since you have chosen to use an IMAP server, and you have chosen to use
local folders as well as folders on the server, you need to select which
type of folder is the default.


For example, your system is named <Bold>home</Bold> and the IMAP server
is named <Bold>latte</Bold>.


If you choose folders on the IMAP server as the default, then you will
need to qualify names of local folders. The folder
<Bold>+sample</Bold> will refer to a folder on the IMAP server and
<Bold>{home}+sample</Bold> will refer to a local folder.


If you choose local folders as the default, the folder
<Bold>+sample</Bold> will refer to a local folder and you must specify
<Bold>{latte}+sample</Bold> to refer to a folder on the IMAP server.


§

[CARD] ishmail.prefWin.saveRC.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Default Save Folder
This parameter determines which folder is used when you use the <bold>Save to Default Folder</bold> function or a message, or group of messages.


Choices for the default folder are:


<bold><italic><bold>Always to:</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>A single folder name is specified, which is used every time you save a message.


Click the <bold>Always to:</bold> radio button and fill in the folder name to select this option. The default folder name is <fixed>+mbox</fixed>.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>By User:</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The folder name is based on the name of the person (<bold>user</bold>) who sent you the message. In this case you also need to specify the directory which contains the folder.


For example, if you choose this option and specify <fixed>Mail</fixed> as the directory, when you save mail from <fixed>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net</fixed> it will be saved to <fixed>$HOME/Mail/support</fixed>.


To select this option:


<indent>1.	<indent>Click the <bold>By</bold> radio button


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Click the menu to the right of the <bold>By</bold> button and select <fixed>User</fixed>


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>Fill in the <bold>to directory:</bold> field


</indent></indent></indent><bold><italic><bold>By Address:</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The folder name is based on the full e-mail <bold>address</bold> of the person who sent you the message. This differs from the <bold>user</bold> option in that the <italic>user</italic> name is qualified by the e-mail <italic>domain</italic>. For example, you might receive mail from two users named <fixed>tom</fixed> in different domains, say <fixed>tom@ishmail.com</fixed> and <fixed>tom@widget.co.uk</fixed>. If you saved mail by <bold>user</bold>, mail from both would go to the same folder. Saving mail by <bold>address</bold> would put the mail into different folders: <fixed>$HOME/Mail/tom@ishmail.com</fixed> and <fixed>$HOME/Mail/tom@widget.co.uk</fixed>.


To select this option:


<indent>1.	<indent>Click the <bold>By</bold> radio button


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Click the menu to the right of the <bold>By</bold> button and select <fixed>Address</fixed>


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>Fill in the <bold>to directory:</bold> field


</indent></indent></indent><bold><italic><bold>By Pattern:</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The folder name is based on a pattern matched in the headers of the mail message. See the <bold>Save Patterns Option</bold> for information about defining patterns.


To select this option:


<indent>1.	<indent>Click the <bold>By</bold> radio button


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Click the menu to the right of the <bold>By</bold> button and select <fixed>Pattern</fixed>


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>Fill in the <bold>to directory:</bold> field


</indent></indent><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If the folder name associated with the pattern in the <bold>Save Patterns Option</bold> is a relative name, it is a folder in the directory you specify here. If a fully qualified path name is specified, then the directory name specified here is ignored.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent><bold><italic><bold>By Pattern or User:</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The <bold>Save Patterns</bold> are searched first for a match. If found, the folder used is the one associated with the pattern. If no match, then the folder name is determined by the <fixed>user</fixed> portion of the e-mail address.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>By Pattern or Address:</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The <bold>Save Patterns</bold> are searched first for a match. If found, the folder used is the one associated with the pattern. If no match, then the folder name is determined by the full e-mail <fixed>address</fixed>.


</indent><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If the folder name generated by the <bold>User</bold>, <bold>Address</bold>, or <bold>Pattern</bold> option doesn't already exist, it will be created. The folder type is determined by the default specified in the <bold>Folder Preferences</bold> option.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

