§

[CARD] ishmail.sendPrefWin.encryptSign.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Encryption and Digital Signature Commands
There are two features available for increasing the security and
insuring the integrity of mail messages you create:
<Bold><Italic>Encryption</Italic></Bold> and <Bold><Italic>Digital
Signatures</Italic></Bold>. 


<Italic>Encryption</Italic> of a message renders the body of the message
unreadable to anyone who does not have the correct key for decoding the
information. A <Italic>digital signature</Italic> is similar to a
sophisticated <Italic>checksum</Italic>, which can be used to verify
that the content of the message body is unchanged from when it was
created and signed. The signature also can be used to validate the
identity of the sender.


Encryption and digital signatures can be used with either MIME messages
or with plain (non-MIME) messages. There is a draft Internet standard
proposed for integration of PGP (<Italic>Pretty Good Privacy</Italic>)
with MIME, and Ishmail implements this draft standard.


<Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> The
<Bold><Italic>ishmail</Italic></Bold> package
<X-Color><Param>red</Param>does not</X-Color> include any encryption
technology. You must supply your own encryption commands. U.S. laws
strictly regulate export of encryption technology.

</Indent>

<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> contains several features which
facilitate integration with external encryption and digital signature
programs. The <Bold>Composition</Bold> and <Bold>Reading</Bold> windows
have hooks which allow the body of a message to be sent to an external
command for appropriate action. Also, a set of shell scripts are
included in the <Fixed><Bold>bin</Bold></Fixed> sub-directory of where
<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> was installed. Functions were
implemented in shell <Italic>wrapper</Italic> scripts for three main
reasons: 


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold> This <Indent>allows customization of the
function to handle different encryption technologies (the reference
technology used is PGP).</Indent> 


<Bold><<></Bold> Function <Indent>can be easily updated as Internet
standards for handling encryption evolve.</Indent> 


<Bold><<></Bold> The <Indent>actual encryption programs cannot be
included with the <Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> package, due to
export and licensing restrictions.


</Indent></Indent>  

The shell scripts include:


<Bold><Italic>ishdecrypt

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Send a message to an external command, such as
PGP, for decryption and/or signature verification. This is used for
messages which are <Italic>not</Italic> in MIME format.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>ishencrypt

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Send a message to an external command, such as
PGP, for encryption and/or digital signature. This is used for messages
which are <Italic>not</Italic> in MIME format.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>ishencryptmime

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Send a message to an external command, such as
PGP, for encryption. This is used for messages in MIME format.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>showpgp

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Send a message to an external command, such as
PGP, for decryption. This is used for messages in MIME format.

</Indent>

<Bold><Italic>showpgpsign

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Send a message to an external command, such as
PGP, for decryption and signature verification. This is used for
messages in MIME format.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>statrun

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Run a command and gather output statistics in a
file.

</Indent>

<Bold><Italic>xtermexec

</Italic></Bold><Indent>Run a command using an
<Fixed><Bold>xterm</Bold></Fixed>, and gather output statistics.

</Indent>

<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> The
<Indent>last two shell scripts compensate for the inability to gather
information about the completion of a command run in an
<Fixed><Bold>xterm</Bold></Fixed>. They do have anything to with
encryption, but are necessary for finding out the results of running
PGP.

</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>

[CARD] ishmail.editExcerptPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Excerpts in a Reply
Select <bold>Excerpt More</bold> to mark text as an <italic>excerpt</italic>. You typically do this to highlight part of your message that is copied from another message. Excerpts can be nested, to indicate, for example, a reply to a reply. Select <bold>Excerpt Less</bold> to remove one level of nesting, or turn off excerpting if at the top level.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> displays an excerpt as indented text with characters marking the left margin. The default character is a greater-than sign, <fixed>></fixed>. You can change this using the <bold>Reply/Forward Preferences</bold> dialog.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  The excerpt characters are not actually put into the message text, but rather attribute tags are inserted. How the excerpt is displayed depends on the mail tool the recipient is using. If the recipient is not using a MIME-capable tool, the tag <fixed><<excerpt></fixed> will be seen at the beginning of the excerpt and the tag <fixed><</excerpt></fixed> will be seen at the end.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you are sending mail to someone who you know doesn't have a MIME-capable mail tool, you can click the <bold>Plain Text</bold> button in the <bold>Composition</bold> window and the MIME <fixed><<excerpt></fixed> tags will be replaced with the characters as they appear in the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

