If you are not sure of a folder name click the <bold>Show list</bold> button. <italic>Ishmail</italic> expands the <bold>Select Folders</bold> box to show you a list of files and directories.


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Select a single folder by clicking on its name in the <bold>Files</bold> list area. 


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Select multiple folders either by shift-clicking the name of each folder, or by dragging the pointer across multiple folders. The folders you select by the <italic>shift-click</italic> or <italic>drag-select</italic> methods must be contiguous.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Select noncontiguous folders by holding the Control key while clicking the left mouse button on each folder to open.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Click the <bold>OK</bold> button to open the folder(s).


</indent></indent>The window also contains two radio buttons which offer the choice to <bold>Open and activate</bold> or <bold>Open only</bold>. If you choose <bold>Open only</bold>, icons representing the folders are added to the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area but the corresponding folder files are not opened. If you choose <bold>Open and activate</bold> the corresponding folder file are opened. The <bold>Open only</bold> option is provided to improve performance if you are adding icons for many folders, or for large folders, to the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area. You can subsequently activate any folder which has been opened.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  <italic>Ishmail</italic> supports three types of folders: <italic>Unix</italic>-style, <italic>MMDF</italic>-style, and <italic>mh</italic>-style. <italic>Unix</italic>-style and <italic>MMDF</italic>-style folders are files which contain one or more mail messages. <italic>mh</italic>-style folders are directories which contain one or more files, each of which is a single mail message. If you are using <italic>mh</italic>-style folders, you will see their names in <italic>both</italic> the <bold>Directories</bold> list and the <bold>Folders</bold> list. You can open an <italic>mh</italic>-style folder from either list, but it is preferable to open from the <bold>Folders</bold> list.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can use a <fixed>+</fixed> (plus sign) or <fixed>=</fixed> (equal sign) at the beginning of the name to refer to you folder directory. For example: <fixed>=folder</fixed> is the same as <fixed>$HOME/Mail/folder</fixed>.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you type a relative path name, it is resolved relative to your home directory. For example: <fixed>dir/folder</fixed> is the same as <fixed>$HOME/dir/folder</fixed>.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can use wildcard characters and shell environment variables in the names, which are expanded by your login shell. For example: <fixed>$HOME/Mail/ishmail*</fixed> will open all folders with names beginning with <italic>ishmail</italic> in you <fixed>$HOME/Mail</fixed> directory.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can refer to multiple folders by typing a carriage return between names.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you are not using <italic>mh</italic>-style mail folders you may find it confusing to see folder directories in the both the <bold>Directories</bold> list and in the <bold>Folders</bold> list of the <bold>Select Folders</bold> dialog. Conversely, if you are using <italic>mh</italic>-style folders you may find it confusing to see non-directory files in the <bold>Folders</bold> list. Using the <bold>Folder Preferences</bold>  option, you can control which types of names are shown in the <bold>Folders</bold> list.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

