[CARD] ishmail.folderPrefWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Folder Preferences Option
The <bold>Folders ...</bold> option lets you change the way mail folders are handled and change the way folder names are shown in the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area of the <bold><italic>Main</italic></bold> window. 


Things that can be changed include:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Choice of folder icons


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Sort order of folder names


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Default data type when creating new folders


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   How folder names are presented in file selection dialogs


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Folders to open at start-up


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Whether to remember which folders were open upon exit


</indent></indent>
<bigger><bold><underline>Folder Icons</underline></bold></bigger>


By default, folder names are shown using icon labels. You can choose to use smaller icons instead, so that more names can be visible in the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area without requiring scroll bars. Or, you can choose to eliminate the icons altogether and just show the folder names, which results in a very compact list of names.


Toggle <fixed>Off</fixed> the <bold>Sort Folders</bold> button to show folder icons in the order they are opened. By default, this button is <fixed>On</fixed> and folder icons are sorted alphabetically by folder name.



<bigger><bold><underline>Folder Type</underline></bold></bigger>


When you create a new folder you can choose from one of three different formats for the folder. Your choices are:


<bold><italic>Unix (<italic>mailx</italic>-style)</italic></bold>

<indent>This is the default on most <italic>Unix</italic> systems. Your InBox folder most likely has this format. Each folder is a file containing zero or more messages. Message boundaries are marked by a line starting with the word "<fixed>From</fixed>" followed by a blank space.


</indent><bold><italic>MH-style</italic></bold>

<indent>This is the folder type supported by the <italic>mh</italic> program, and related programs (<italic>xmh</italic>, <italic>exmh</italic>, etc.). It is also to format for <italic>USENET</italic> news groups. Each folder is a directory containing zero or more files, each of which contains one message.


</indent><bold><italic>MMDF-style</italic></bold>

<indent>This is the folder type supported by the <italic>MMDF</italic> program. Similar to <italic>Unix</italic> folders, each folder is a file containing zero or more messages. The difference is that in <italic>MMDF</italic> folders the message boundary is a line containing four <fixed>Ctrl-A</fixed> characters.


</indent>All <italic>Ishmail</italic> functions work with each folder type. Which folder type you select is determined mainly by compatibility with other mail programs. For example, if you have been using <italic>xmh</italic> and want to switch to <italic>Ishmail</italic> you will most likely choose to work with MH-style folders.


Toggle <fixed>Off</fixed> the <bold>Confirm type</bold> button if you intend to always use the same folder type, and don't want to be asked about it each time you create a folder.


This button is also found in the <bold>Confirmations</bold> dialog. You can set it either place.



<bigger><bold><underline>Showing Folder Names in File Selection Dialogs</underline></bold></bigger>


<italic>Ishmail</italic> uses a common <bold>File Selection</bold> dialog for specifying file names or folder names. It contains a list showing directory names and a list showing file names.


When you use the <bold>File Selection</bold> dialog to choose a folder name, the names of MH folders appear in both lists. If you select an MH folder name from the <bold>Directory Name</bold> list, it is treated as a directory rather than a folder. If you select an MH folder name from the <bold>File Name List</bold>, it is treated as a mail folder. 


Showing the name in both lists can be confusing. If you are not using MH folders, you may want to toggle <fixed>Off</fixed> the <bold>Show MH folders</bold> button so that directory names will not appear in the <bold>Folder Name</bold> list. 


Conversely, if you are using MH folders you may want to Toggle <fixed>Off</fixed> the <bold>Show Unix and MMDF</bold> folders button so that only directory names (MH folder names) will appear in the <bold>Folder Name list</bold>.



<bigger><bold><underline>Initial Folders</underline></bold></bigger>


You can explicitly specify folders which should be automatically opened when <italic>Ishmail</italic> starts up, by entering their names in the <bold>Initial Folders:</bold> field.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  A <fixed>+</fixed> character or an <fixed>=</fixed> character at the beginning of a name is a synonym for your default folder directory, typically <fixed>$HOME/Mail</fixed>.


</indent></indent></indentright>Or, you can implicitly specify folders which should be automatically opened when <italic>Ishmail</italic> starts up, by toggling on the <bold>Remember folders on exit:</bold> button. If you do so, any folders which are open at the time you exit <italic>Ishmail</italic> will be automatically opened the next time you start the program.


§

[CARD] ishmail.queryFolderTypeWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Folder Type Selection
<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> supports three types of mail
folders, <Italic>Unix</Italic>, <Italic>mh</Italic>, and
<Italic>MMDF.</Italic> The type you select depends on what other mail
programs you are using. <Italic>Unix</Italic> folders are the most
common type.


<X-Color><Param>Green</Param>TIP:</X-Color> For a more complete
description of folder types, see the Help Card for the
<Bold>Folders</Bold> window, from the <Bold>Main</Bold> window
<Bold>Options</Bold> menu.


When using an <Bold>IMAP</Bold> server you have an additional option.
You can indicate that all the folders you use are located on the server
system. Click the <Bold>None</Bold> button if this is what you want to
do. Or, you can use folders located on either your local system or on
the server.


<X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> If you decide to use local
folders, you must include the server name when accessing a folder on
the<Bold> IMAP</Bold> server. For example: Assume the server name is
<Fixed><Bold>latte</Bold></Fixed>. The folder
<Fixed><Bold>+sample</Bold></Fixed> refers to
<Fixed><Bold>$HOME/Mail/sample</Bold></Fixed> on the server
<Fixed><Bold>latte</Bold></Fixed>. However, if you choose to access
local folders then <Fixed><Bold>+sample</Bold></Fixed> refers to
<Fixed><Bold>$HOME/Mail/sample</Bold></Fixed> on your local system. You
can still use the folder <Fixed><Bold>sample</Bold></Fixed> from the
server, but you must refer to it as
<Fixed><Bold>{latte}+sample</Bold></Fixed>.

