[CARD] ishmail.folderList.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Folders List
The <bold>Folders</bold> list contains the list of mail folders or files in the current directory. The list is updated each time you enter the name of a different directory in the <bold>Current Directory</bold> text field (and press <fixed>Return</fixed> or press <fixed>Enter</fixed> or click the <bold>Set</bold> button) or when you double-click on a directory in the <bold>Directories</bold> list selection field.


To select a mail folder or file in the <bold>Folders</bold> list, click on its name.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Standard Unix mail folders and <italic>MMDF</italic>-style folders are files containing one or more messages. <italic>Mh</italic>-style folders are directories containing files, each containing one message. If you are using <italic>mh</italic>-style folders, you will see their names in <italic>both</italic> the <bold>Folders</bold> list and the <bold>Directories</bold> list. If you select and open an <italic>mh</italic>-folder name from the <bold>Directories</bold> list, each message in it appears as a mail folder in the <bold>Folders</bold> list. It is preferable to select the <italic>mh</italic>-folder name from the <bold>Folders</bold> list instead, and all the files in the directory are then handled as a single folder.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you are not using <italic>mh</italic>-style mail folders you may find it confusing to see folder directories in the both the <bold>Directories</bold> list and in the <bold>Folders</bold> list of the <bold>Select Folders</bold> dialog. Conversely, if you are using <italic>mh</italic>-style folders you may find it confusing to see non-directory files in the <bold>Folders</bold> list. Using the <bold>Folder Preferences</bold> option, you can control which types of names are shown in the <bold>Folders</bold> list.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

