There are two check box buttons below the <bold>Family</bold> column. Either or both of these may be toggled <fixed>On</fixed>. These buttons are:


<bold><italic><bold>Show fixed-width fonts</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The <bold>Family</bold> list should include fonts where each character has the same horizontal width.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Show proportional-width fonts</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The <bold>Family</bold> list should include fonts where different characters have different horizontal widths. For example, the lower case <fixed>l</fixed> character will be much narrower than an upper case <fixed>M</fixed>.


</indent>There are two radio button below the <bold>Style</bold> column. Either one or the other must be toggled <fixed>On</fixed>. These buttons are:


<bold><italic><bold>Show size in pixels</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The <bold>Size</bold> list should represent the number of pixels. A common pixel density for monitors is 100 dots (pixels) per inch, so a size of <fixed>33</fixed> would indicate the font is about one third inch tall.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Show size in points</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The <bold>Size</bold> list should represent point size. There are 72 point per inch, so a size of <fixed>24</fixed> would indicate the font is about one third inch tall.


</indent>§

