[CARD] ishmail.msgForward822PB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Forward (encapsulate) Option
Choose <bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold> to forward the current or selected message to one or more recipients. 


The are two similar options, <bold>Forward</bold> and <bold>Resend</bold>. When you <italic>forward</italic> a message you have the opportunity to edit its contents before passing it on. The recipients will see a return address for the message as if you composed and sent it. When you <italic>resend</italic> a message you cannot edit its contents before passing it on, and it will appear to recipients as if it came from the original sender rather than from you. (Note that a mail header is added indicating that the message was resent, and by whom.)


When you click <bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold>, <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Composition</bold> window. The <bold>Composition</bold> window contains a recipient field, subject field, and <bold>Message</bold> area. <italic>Ishmail</italic> automatically fills in the <bold><italic>Subject</italic></bold> field. In the <bold>Message</bold> area, the message being forwarded will appear as an icon.


<bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold> differs from <bold>Forward</bold> in that when you Forward an Encapsulated message, the contents of the original message appear as an icon (an attachment) in the <bold>Composition</bold> window, rather than expanding the forwarded message in-line. This better preserves the original message and its attributes, especially if the forwarded message is itself a MIME message. In either case, you can edit the forwarded message before sending it.


§

[CARD] ishmail.msgForwardPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Forward Option
Choose <bold>Forward</bold> to forward the current or selected message to one or more recipients. 


The are two similar options, <bold>Forward</bold> and <bold>Resend</bold>. When you <italic>forward</italic> a message you have the opportunity to edit its contents before passing it on. The recipients will see a return address for the message as if you composed and sent it. When you <italic>resend</italic> a message you cannot edit its contents before passing it on, and it will appear to recipients as if it came from the original sender rather than from you. (Note that a mail header is added indicating that the message was resent, and by whom.)


When you click <bold>Forward</bold>, <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Composition</bold> window. The <bold>Composition</bold> window contains a recipient field, subject field, and <bold>Message</bold> area.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> automatically fills in the <bold><italic>Subject</italic></bold> field and the <bold>Message</bold> area with the text from the original message.


<bold>Forward</bold> differs from <bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold> in that when you Forward a message, the contents of the original message appear as text (and possibly attachments) in the <bold>Composition</bold> window. 


When you choose <bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold> the original message will appear as an icon (an attachment) in the <bold>Composition</bold> window. This better preserves the original message and its attributes, especially if the forwarded message is itself a MIME message. In either case, you can edit the forwarded message before sending it.


§

[CARD] ishmail.optGroupAliasPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Group Aliases Option
Choose the <bold>Aliases</bold> option to specify <italic>aliases</italic> and associated mail addresses in your group's alias database.


An alias is a shortened name or alphanumeric string that represents an electronic mail address. For example, you can specify the alias "Rob" to represent the electronic mail address "Robert_Smith@oakcreek4.sps.lat.com" in <italic>Ishmail's</italic> alias database. Then, when you compose a message to Robert Smith, instead of entering the complete 34-character mail address, you simply type <fixed>Rob</fixed> at the <bold><italic>To:</italic></bold> prompt in the message header.  


When you click <bold>Group Aliases ...</bold>, <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Edit Alias</bold> window. Use the <bold>Edit Alias</bold> window to add, change, or delete aliases and their associated mail addresses. 


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Aliases are used in the <bold>To:</bold>, <bold>Cc:</bold>, and <bold>Bcc:</bold> fields when composing a message. See the <bold><italic>Composition</italic></bold> window help card for more information.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

