§

[CARD] ishmail.queryImapWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] IMAP Server
<Bold>IMAP</Bold> is a network protocol which is used for working with
mail folders on a remote system. Typically, <Bold>IMAP</Bold> is used
when you are connecting to a remote server over a slow link, such as a
phone line.


<Italic>Internet Access Providers</Italic> usually offer remote folder
support via  <Bold>POP</Bold> protocol or <Bold>IMAP</Bold> protocol.


<X-Color><Param>Green</Param>TIP:</X-Color> If you have a choice,
<Bold>IMAP</Bold> is preferable to <Bold>POP</Bold>.


<Bold>IMAP</Bold> is a newer protocol than <Bold>POP</Bold>, and was
designed to fix some of the shortcomings of <Bold>POP</Bold>. Three main
improvements are:


<Bold><<> IMAP</Bold> <Indent>does not move all your messages from the
server to your local machine. Instead, they remain on the server. This
makes it possible to continue to access your mail if you switch to a
different client system. 

</Indent>

<Bold><<> IMAP</Bold> <Indent>only downloads message headers when
building the message list. This can greatly improve performance. Also,
IMAP downloads messages piece by piece, rather than pulling down the
whole message. This can make it much quicker to read large messages (the
next piece is being downloaded while you read the current piece of the
message).


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold> Using <Indent><Bold>IMAP</Bold>, you can work
with multiple folders on the server, and even work with folders on
multiple servers. <Bold>POP</Bold> only works with one folder, your
InBox, on one server.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> There <Indent>are
two version of the <Bold>IMAP</Bold> protocol, <Bold>IMAP2</Bold> and
<Bold>IMAP4</Bold>. Ishmail works with either version.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>Green</Param>TIP:</X-Color> If you do not set
up <Bold>IMAP</Bold> access now, you can do so later using the <Bold>Application
Preference</Bold> window, from the <Bold>Main</Bold> window
<Bold>Options</Bold> menu.

§

[CARD] ishmail.imapTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] IMAP Server Name
Use this field to name the <Bold><Italic>IMAP server</Italic></Bold> from
which you will access your mail folder(s).


IMAP servers are typically used to serve mail folders to users connected
to the network over a slow link such as a phone line. <Italic>Internet
Access Providers</Italic> usually support IMAP and/or POP servers for
this purpose. 


<Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> If you have more
than one IMAP server on your network, or if you keep some of your
folders on your local disk, then you need to qualify folder names with
the server name. For example, if you want to open a folder called
<Bold><Italic>outgoing</Italic></Bold>, which is in your
<Bold><Italic>$HOME/Mail</Italic></Bold> directory on an IMAP server
named <Bold><Italic>latte</Italic></Bold>, you would use this name in
the <Bold><Italic>Open Folder</Italic></Bold> dialog:


<Indent><Fixed><Bold>{latte}+outgoing

</Indent>

</Bold></Fixed>Or, you can use full path names with a IMAP server name,
for example:


<Indent><Fixed><Bold>{latte}/u/me/outgoing

</Bold></Fixed></Indent>

Use the <Bold><Italic>Options->Folders</Italic></Bold> window to specify
whether some of your folders are kept on a local disk.</Indent>


§

[CARD] ishmail.queryImapServerWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] IMAP Server Name
Since you have selected to use the <Bold>IMAP</Bold> protocol, you must
provide the name of the mail server. Ask your system administrator or
your <Italic>Internet Access Provider</Italic> if you are not sure what
name to use.


This will be the server from which
<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> accesses your
<Bold>InBox</Bold> folder. You can access other folders on the server,
using the <Bold>Open Folder</Bold> window from the
<Bold>Folders</Bold> menu.


<X-Color><Param>Green</Param>TIP:</X-Color> If you want to access
folders from another server, you can specify the server name as part of
the folder name. For example, to access the folder
<Fixed><Bold>$HOME/Mail/ishmail-notes</Bold></Fixed> from the server
<Fixed><Bold>latte</Bold></Fixed> use this folder name:


<Indent><Fixed><Bold>{latte}+ishmail-notes


</Bold></Fixed></Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> You
<Indent>have the option of using mail folders on your local system as
well as on the server. If you choose to use local folders, then you
must<Italic>always</Italic> use the server name when accessing a folder
from the server. For example, the folder name
<Fixed><Bold>+ishmail-notes</Bold></Fixed> refers to a folder name on
the server if you are <Bold>not</Bold> using local folders. Otherwise it
refers to a local folder.</Indent>

