[CARD] ishmail.mailPrefWin.mailTypeFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Mail Preferences - Outgoing mail type
Since MIME messages ultimately encode all data as plain ASCII text, MIME formatted messages can be read using any mail tool. However, the data format may not be very readable. The <bold>Outgoing mail</bold> type option lets you enhance MIME message readability for people using non-MIME tools. There are three options:


<bold><italic><bold>Plain</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The message is sent with all MIME formatting and non-ASCII data stripped from it. This is the ultimate in backward compatibility though, of course, you loose all the advanced MIME features.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  This is a good choice for the default option, since messages will be sent in backward-compatible format. If you add something to your message, such as a formatting change or an attachment, which requires MIME capability <italic>Ishmail</italic> will offer you the chance to change to the <bold>MIME</bold> option before the message is sent.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent><bold><italic><bold>MIME</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The message is formatted and sent as a MIME message, even if it contains only plain ASCII text.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Both</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>The message is formatted and sent as a MIME message, and a <italic>plain text alternative</italic> is included in front. The plain text alternative is the message text with all MIME attributes stripped, like the <bold>Plain</bold> option. Recipients without MIME-capability will see the plain text alternative, and can ignore the following copy of the message with encoded MIME data. MIME-capable mail tools will automatically skip the plain text alternative part and utilize the MIME encoded data. So, this is the best of both, allowing maximum backward compatibility while not loosing MIME capability. However, the message can be much larger, up to double the size, due to the duplicate copies of the message in different formats.


</indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.mailPrefWin.deadTB.ctx.HLP
