[CARD] ishmail.mailcap.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Mailcap File
The <bold>mailcap</bold> file specifies which commands are used to create, display, and print the various data types found in MIME messages.


Ishmail will look for a file called <fixed>mailcap</fixed> in the <fixed>lib</fixed> subdirectory of where the program was installed. For example, on SVR4 systems this is <fixed>/opt/ishmail/x.y/lib/mailcap</fixed>, where <fixed>x.y</fixed> is the release and version of the program.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> also attempts to read a user-provided <fixed>mailcap</fixed> file in the user's home directory. This file is <fixed>$HOME/.mailcap</fixed>. This file does not have to exist. But, if it does, its entries will take precedence over entries of the same type in the system mailcap file.


The syntax of a mailcap file is fairly simple and straightforward. Any line that starts with <fixed>#</fixed> is a comment. Blank lines are ignored. Otherwise, each line defines a single mailcap entry for a single content type. Long lines may be continued by ending them with a backslash character, <fixed>\</fixed>.


Each individual mailcap entry consists of a content-type specification, a command to execute, and (possibly) a set of optional flag values. For example, a very simple mailcap entry might look like this:


<fixed><bold>image/gif; xloadimage %s</bold></fixed>


The optional flags can be used to specify additional information about the mail-handling command. For example:


<fixed><bold>image/gif; xloadimage %s; label="A GIF Image"</bold></fixed>


can be added to use as a default label to display when a MIME message arrives with an image/gif type, that provides no description of itself.


The type field (image/gif, in the above example) is simply any legal content type name, as defined by <italic><underline>Internet RFC 1341 (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extension)</underline></italic>. In practice, this is almost any string. It is the string that will be matched against the "Content-type" header to decide if this is the mailcap entry that matches the current message. 


Additionally, the type field may specify a subtype or a wildcard to match all subtypes (for example, "image/*"). A wild card definition should follow specific definitions, because <italic>Ishmail</italic> will attempt to match the first entry it finds.


The command field is any UNIX command ("xloadimage %s" in the above example), and is used to specify the interpreter for the given type of message. Semicolons and backslashes within the command must be quoted with backslashes. If the command contains "%s", those two characters will be replaced by the name of a file that contains the body of the message. If it contains "%t", those two characters will be replaced by the content-type field, including the subtype, if any. (That is, if the content-type was "image/jpeg; opt1=something-else", then "%t" would be replaced by "image/jpeg".) 


If the command field contains "%{" followed by a parameter name and a closing "}", then all those characters will be replaced by the value of the value of the named parameter, if any, from the value of the Content-type header. Thus, in the earlier example, "%{opt1}" will be replaced by "something-else". If a parameter is specified for the command, and the body part does not have a value for it, then "" (two double quotes representing the empty string) is substituted on the command line.


If the command contains a "%e", those two characters will be replaced by the value of the Content-Transfer-Encoding, if there is one. This is useful particularly for external-body types, and the command needs to decode the retrieved body.


There are two additional built-in parameters; %{ruser} and %{rpwd}. The first, <bold><italic>ruser</italic></bold>, is where a user-supplied user account name is substituted on the command line. This is commonly used for external-body types that use "ftp" as an access-type. The <bold><italic>rpwd</italic></bold> parameter is for the accompanying password.


If no "%s" appears in the command field, then instead of placing the message body in a temporary file, <italic>Ishmail</italic> passes the body to the command on the standard input. This is helpful in saving <fixed>/tmp</fixed> file space, but can be problematic for window-oriented applications under some window systems such as <italic>MGR</italic>.


The "notes=xxx" field is an uninterpreted string that is used to specify the name of the person who installed this entry in the mailcap file. (The "xxx" may be replaced by any text string.)


The "test=xxx" field is a command that is executed to determine whether the mailcap line actually applies. That is, if the content-type field matches the content-type on the message, but a "test=" field is present, then the test must succeed before the mailcap line is considered to "match" the message being viewed. The command may be any UNIX command, using the same syntax and the same %-escapes as for the viewing command, as described above. A command is considered to succeed if it exits with a zero exit status, and to fail otherwise.


The "print=xxx" field is a command to use when you want to print the file. For instance application/postscript type could have an entry:


<fixed><bold>application/postscript; ghostview %s; print=lpr -P ps_printer</bold></fixed>


The "textualnewlines" field can be used in the rather obscure case where <italic>Ishmail's</italic> default rules for treating newlines in base64-encoded data are unsatisfactory. By default, <italic>Ishmail</italic> translates CRLF to the local newline character in decoded base64 output if the content-type is "text" (any subtype), but will not do so otherwise. A mailcap entry with a field of "textualnewlines=1" will force such translation for the specified content-type, while "textualnewlines=0" will guarantee that the translation does not take place even for textual content-types.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> handles the following types automatically, thus negating a need for mailcap entries for text/plain, text/richtext, multipart/ mixed, multipart/digest, multipart/alternative, multipart/parallel, message/rfc822, and message/partial. But this does not preclude creating <italic>mailcap</italic> entries for these types if, for some reason, you'd rather not use the built-in presentation mechanisms for these types.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> has a default entry for message/external-body in the mailcap shipped with the program. It is recommended that this entry not be changed.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> also has default entries for image/gif and audio/basic. However, if you have a better application for presenting these types, make the change there.


§

[CARD] ishmail.mainShell.win.HLP
[TITLE] Main Window
<italic>Ishmail's</italic> main window provides access to many of the features of the <italic>Ishmail</italic> electronic mail utility. From the main window, you can view your mail folders and their contents, and perform a number of administrative tasks on your folders, messages, and mail environment. To handle these tasks, you use:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   menu bar


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   open folders window


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   folder contents area


</indent></indent>
<bigger><bold><underline>Menu Bar</underline></bold></bigger>


The menu bar contains five pull-down menus from which you choose options for managing messages, folders, and your <italic>Ishmail</italic> environment. To open a menu, click the menu title in the menu bar:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   <bold>File</bold> 


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   <bold>Folder</bold> 


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   <bold>Message</bold> 


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   <bold>Options</bold>


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   <bold>Help</bold> 


</indent></indent>
<bigger><bold><underline>Open Folders Area</underline></bold></bigger>


The <bold>Open Folders</bold> area displays the default <bold><italic>In-box</italic></bold> mail folder file and any other optional mail folder files you have opened. Each mail folder is represented by an icon. Your <bold><italic>in-box</italic></bold> folder is shown as a mailbox icon. Other mail folders are shown with manilla folder icons.


When you start the program, <italic>Ishmail</italic> automatically opens the <bold><italic>In-box</italic></bold> and displays its mailbox icon in the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area. The contents of the <bold><italic>In-box</italic></bold> are listed in the <bold>Folder</bold> contents area directly below the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area.


There is a <bold>Button</bold> at the lower right corner of the <bold><italic>Open Folders</italic></bold> area. Click and drag this <bold>Button</bold> up or down to change the size of the <bold><italic>Open Folders</italic></bold> area. You can, for example, make the <bold><italic>Open Folders</italic></bold> area small so that only icon titles are shown, leaving more room in the window for the <bold><italic>Folder Contents</italic></bold> area.


When the <bold><italic>Open Folders</italic></bold> area is smaller than the icons, a <bold>Scroll Bar</bold> is shown on the right side. 



<bigger><bold><underline>Folder Contents Area</underline></bold></bigger>


The <bold>Folder Contents Area</bold> of the main window lists the mail messages contained in the mail folder that is currently <italic>active</italic>. The list contains status information about each of the messages in the active folder including, whether the message is new, whether it has been read, when it arrived, and who sent it.


The width of the columns is automatically changed to fit the widest item. However, if you wish to control the width of the columns you may do so in either of two ways. The easiest way is to click a <bold>vertical separator bar</bold> above the top of the <bold><italic>Folder Contents</italic></bold> area and drag it to the left or to the right. You will immediately see the results as you release the mouse button. Note that you must click the separator bar <italic>above</italic> the Folder Contents area, not the separator bar inside the message list.


The second way to change the width of the columns is to use the <bold>Edit Message List</bold> window, which can be selected from the <bold>Options</bold> pull-down menu. This window also lets you turn off the individual message list icons, which results in tighter spacing so that more messages can be seen in the <bold>Folder Contents Area</bold>.


The <bold><italic>Folder Contents Area</italic></bold> has both vertical and horizontal <bold>scroll bars</bold>. The vertical <bold>scroll bar</bold> lets you scroll the list of messages forward or back. You can use the <bold><italic>Sort</italic></bold> window, selected from the <bold><italic>Options</italic></bold> pull-down menu, to control the order of the messages in the list.


The horizontal <bold>scroll bar</bold> lets you see parts of the message list past the left or right margins of the <bold><italic>Folder Contents Area</italic></bold>.



<bigger><bold><underline>Getting More Information</underline></bold></bigger>


To get more information about <italic>Ishmail</italic> components:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Move the pointer onto the component. If <bold>QuickHelp</bold> is available for the component, a terse description of the component appears in the message area near the bottom of the window.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Select <bold>On Context</bold> from the <bold>Help</bold> menu. The pointer turns into a question mark. To display the Help message for a specific component, place the question mark on the component and click. 


</indent></indent>§


[CARD] ishmail.mainShell.folderCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Main Window - Folder Menu
The <bold>Folder</bold> menu contains options for managing your mail folders. From the <bold>Folder</bold> menu, you can make a mail folder active, create new mail folders, open, close, and save changes to mail folders, and select or deselect mail folders. To see the <bold>Folder</bold> menu options, click the <bold>Folder</bold> button, or type Meta-L.


Message folders are files that contain one or more mail messages. The system folder, called the <bold>In-box</bold>, is the default mailbox. <italic>Ishmail</italic> automatically opens your in-box when you start the program, and stores incoming mail messages there until you delete them or move them to a different folder. Each <italic>Ishmail</italic> user has a unique <bold>In-box</bold>. 


You can create other folders and use them for organizing messages. The folders can exist anywhere you have read/write privileges, and you can assign them any name within the limits of your operating system's file naming rules. The file system directory structure can provide a hierarchy for collections of folders.


Security and access privileges for folders are the same as those provided for files in the UNIX file system. <italic>Ishmail</italic> does not provide any additional access controls or security.


§

[CARD] ishmail.mainShell.msgCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Main Window - Message Menu
Use the <bold>Message</bold> menu to manage messages selected the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area. To see the <bold>Message</bold> menu options, click <bold>Message</bold> in the menu bar, or type Meta-M. 


The behavior of many options in the <bold>Message</bold> menu can be controlled by setting preferences with the <bold>Preferences</bold> option of the main window <bold>Options</bold> menu. 


<bold>Message</bold> menu options are:


<bold><italic><bold>Compose New</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Open the <bold>Composition</bold> window to compose a mail message. 


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Reply</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reply to the current or selected message. When you click <bold>Reply</bold>, <italic>Ishmail</italic> opens a cascading menu from which you choose one of four reply options:


<bold><italic><bold>To sender</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reply to the originator of the message. Do not include the original message. 


This selection launches the Composition window with the <bold><italic>To:</italic></bold> field already filled in with the address or alias of the message originator. The composition field is blank.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>To sender (include message)</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reply to the originator of the message and include the original message. 


</indent><bold><italic><bold>To all</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reply to the originator of the message and to all recipients of the message. Do not include the original message. 


</indent><bold><italic><bold>To all (include message)</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reply to the originator and all recipients of the message and include the original message. 


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Replies that are generated using either of the Reply <bold><italic>To all</italic></bold> options are not sent to recipients who were blind copied via the <bold><italic>Bcc</italic></bold> field by the original sender. 


</indent></indent></indentright></indent></indent><bold><italic><bold>Forward</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Forwards the current or selected message to other recipients. The <bold>Composition</bold> window is opened, containing the text of the message being forwarded.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Forwards the current or selected message to other recipients. The <bold>Composition</bold> window is opened, containing an icon which represents the message being forwarded. You can double click on the icon to edit that message. The <bold>Forward (encapsulate)</bold> option differs from the <bold>Forward</bold> option in that the message is forwarded as an intact RFC822 mail message, rather than included as text of a new message.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Resend</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Forwards the current or selected message to other recipients. The <bold>Composition</bold> window is opened, containing the text of the message being forwarded. However, the message text cannot be modified. Only the header fields (<bold>To:</bold>, <bold>Cc:</bold>, etc.) can be modified. This option differs from the other <bold>Forward</bold> options in that the forwarded message appears to the recipient to have come from the original sender rather than from you.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Save</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Save the current or selected message(s) to the default save file specified in the <bold>Mail Preferences</bold> window. When you click <bold>Save</bold>, the selected message is saved to the default save file and the icon for the selected message changes into an icon of a folder that now contains the message. An asterisk in the message marker field adjacent to the icon indicates that the message has been saved to the default save file. 


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  To change the name of the default save file use the <bold>Preferences</bold> option in the <bold>Options</bold> menu.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent><bold><italic><bold>Save to</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Save the current or selected message to a mail folder or file that you specify. You can either <bold>Move</bold> the message or <bold>Copy</bold> the message to the specified destination.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Print</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Send the current or selected message(s) to a designated printer. When you click <bold>Print</bold>, the <bold>Print Message</bold> window appears, in which you specify how message headers are to be handled.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Filter</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Specify parameters for routing the selected message or group of messages through an external filter or command of your choice. 


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Mark for Deletion</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Mark the selected message or group of messages for deletion upon the next <bold>save changes</bold> operation or upon exiting the program with the save changes option selected.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Undelete last</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reverse the most recent <bold>mark for deletion</bold> operation. This option restores the last message deleted. It also restores multiple messages if they were deleted as a group during the last delete operation.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Undelete selected</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reverses the <bold>mark for deletion</bold> operation on one or more selected messages. This option is not available if the <bold>Hide messages marked for deletion</bold> option is in effect.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Undelete from list</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Recover one or more messages. This option is only available if the <bold>Hide messages marked for deletion</bold> option is in effect. This option moves messages from the "hidden" list back into the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> viewing area upon message restoration.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Read</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Display the selected message in the <bold>Reading</bold> window.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If the <bold>Reading</bold> window is already open, Ishmail automatically replaces the text of the previously displayed message with the text of the current message.


</indent></indent></indentright>To use multiple <bold>Reading</bold> windows simultaneously, pin the <bold>Reading</bold> window to retain using the pushpin in the upper right-hand corner of the window. 


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Read next</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Display the next undeleted message, after the current selected message, in the <bold>Reading</bold> window.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Read previous</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Display the next undeleted message, before the selected message, in the <bold>Reading</bold> window.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Select All</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Mark all messages as selected.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Deselect All</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Reverse the selection of any or all selected messages.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Search</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Search for specific mail message(s). You can perform a simple search using a single search pattern or you can construct a complex search expression using multiple search patterns. 


</indent>§

