[CARD] ishmail.openSelectWin.selectTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Open Selected Folders - Name Field
Enter one or more names of folders to be opened. Multiple path names are separated by pressing the Return (or Enter) key. Wildcard characters and environment variable names, recognized by your login shell, can be used.


Press Ctrl-Return or click the <bold>OK</bold> button to cause the folders to be opened.


§

[CARD] ishmail.openSelectWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Open Selected Folders Window
Use the <bold>Select Folders</bold> window to select one or more folders to open.


If you know the name of the folder you wish to open, enter the name in the <bold>Selected Folders</bold> field and click <bold>OK</bold> (or press <fixed>Ctrl-Return</fixed> or <fixed>Ctrl-Enter</fixed>).


You can use wild card characters in the file name. Wild cards will be expanded using the shell specified by your <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> environment variable, or by <bold><italic>/bin/sh</italic></bold> if <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> is not set. If the wild card pattern returns multiple names, all these files will be opened.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> recognizes two wild card characters in addition to those handled by the shell. If the first character of a file name is a plus (<fixed>+</fixed>) or an equal sign (<fixed>=</fixed>), it is replaced by the name of your folder directory (typically, <bold><italic>$HOME/Mail</italic></bold>).


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can use a command, or sequence of commands, in this field if you enclose them with back-quote (`) characters. For example, to open all folders in the current directory and its subdirectories, do the following:


</indent></indent></indentright><fixed><bold>`find . -type f -print`</bold></fixed>


To see the names of existing folders and directories, click the <bold>Show list</bold> button to the right of the <bold>Selected Folders</bold> field. <italic>Ishmail</italic> opens a file list. You can use this expanded folder selection window to navigate within your system's directory structure.


You can choose to open a standard Unix mail folder (used by <bold><italic>mail</italic></bold>, <bold><italic>mailx</italic></bold>, <bold><italic>elm</italic></bold>, etc.) or an MH-style folder (used by <bold><italic>mh</italic></bold>, <bold><italic>xmh</italic></bold>, and <bold><italic>exmh</italic></bold>). Standard Unix mail folders are files which contain one or more messages. MH-style folders are directories which contain files. Each message is in an individual file.


Click on <bold><italic>Show List</italic></bold> to show an expanded window which contains additional fields. Using these additional fields you can navigate in your file system to find and select folders. Use <bold>help on context</bold> to see more information about each.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you are using MH-style folders, folder names appear in both the directory list and folder name list fields.


</indent></indent></indentright>To close the this window without selecting a folder, click <bold>Cancel</bold>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.openSelectWin.activateFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Open/Activate a Folder
If you <italic>open</italic> and <italic>activate</italic> a folder, an icon for it is placed into the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area and the contents of the folder are examined to build a list of messages contained in it.


If you only <italic>open</italic>, but do not <italic>activate</italic>, a folder an icon for it is placed in the <bold>Open Folders</bold> area. When you switch to the folder (by double clicking its icon) a message list will be built at that time.


The <bold>Open only</bold> option is preferred if you are opening several folders at once, since it will be much faster.


§

[CARD] ishmail.queryPopWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] POP Mail Server Option
<Bold>POP</Bold> is a network protocol which is used for working with
mail folders on a remote system. Typically, <Bold>POP</Bold> is used
when you are connecting to a remote server over a slow link, such as a
phone line.


<Italic>Internet Access Providers</Italic> usually offer remote folder
support via  <Bold>POP</Bold> protocol or <Bold>IMAP</Bold> protocol.


<Bold>IMAP</Bold> is a newer, improved protocol but <Bold>POP</Bold> support
is very widespread. <Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> supports both.


<X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> There are two versions of
<Bold>POP</Bold> protocol, <Bold>POP2</Bold> and <Bold>POP3</Bold>.
<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> supports both.

§

[CARD] ishmail.prefWin.popCmdTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] POP Server Command
You can use a full path name if the command's directory is not in your
search path.


You can use <Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> variables, which begin
with a percent symbol (<Bold><Fixed>%</Fixed></Bold>), or shell
variables, which begin with a dollar sign
(<Bold><Fixed>$</Fixed></Bold>). Some useful examples are
<Fixed><Bold>%user</Bold></Fixed> (your mail user name) and
<Fixed><Bold>$MAIL</Bold></Fixed> (the path name of your
<Italic>In-Box</Italic> mail folder).


The default command is:


<Indent><Fixed><Bold>popclient -3 -s -u %user -p %pass -o $MAIL

</Bold></Fixed></Indent>

See the popclient man page on your system for information about the
parameters.


<Indent><X-Color><Param>Yellow</Param>CAUTION:</X-Color> The
<Fixed><Bold>popclient</Bold></Fixed> command as shown above deletes
your mail messages from the server after reading them. Typically, this
is what you want to happen, or else each mail check will result in
another copy of the same messages being read from the server. However,
if there is a problem with appending messages to the folder specified
with the <Bold>-o</Bold> parameter, the messages can be lost. You might
want to use the <Bold>-k</Bold> parameter (<Italic>keep</Italic>, do not
delete, messages on the server) the first time you try using the POP
server, until you are confident that everything is working correctly.

</Indent>

<Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> A side effect of the
popclient deleting all messages on the POP server is that you will not
be able to move to a different machine and still read your mail. The
IMAP protocol was designed to remedy this shortcoming of POP protocol,
which deletes messages after reading them unless the <Bold>-k</Bold> flag
is used. Messages are not deleted from the folder on the IMAP server
until you explicitly delete them. Also, IMAP is optimized to minimize
data traffic on a slow link. For example, your entire mail folder does
<Italic>not</Italic> need to be copied before you are able to look at
the first message, as is the case with POP.


If you have a choice between POP and IMAP protocols, IMAP is a better
choice.

§

[CARD] ishmail.queryPopServerWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] POP Server Configuration
Since you have chosen to use the <Italic>Post Office Protocol
</Italic>(<Bold>POP</Bold>) you must specify the name of the server
which contains your InBox folder. Ask your system administrator or your
<Italic>Internet Access Provider</Italic> if you are not sure of the
name.


There are two versions of POP which are commonly used,
<Bold>POP2</Bold> and <Bold>POP3</Bold>. You must select one to use. If
you're not sure, ask your administrator or select <Bold>POP3</Bold>.


<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> uses an external command to access the POP
server. Typically, this command is called
<Fixed><Bold>popclient</Bold></Fixed>. Specify the name of this command
in the field at the bottom of the window. If the command is not in your
search path, you can specify a full path name (for example,
<Fixed><Bold>/usr/pop/popclient</Bold></Fixed>).


<X-Color><Param>Green</Param>TIP: </X-Color><Indent>You can also specify
parameters for the <Fixed><Bold>popclient</Bold></Fixed> command. A
commonly used on is the <Bold>-k</Bold> flag (see the
<X-Color><Param>red</Param>WARNING: </X-Color>below). For example:


<Fixed><Bold>/usr/bin/popclient -k

</Indent>

</Bold></Fixed><X-Color><Param>Yellow</Param>CAUTION:
</X-Color><Indent>The <Fixed><Bold>popclient</Bold></Fixed> program
copies your entire InBox folder to your local system. Normally it
deletes the messages from the server after it copies them. This is
desirable since if the messages were not deleted they would be
downloaded again the next time <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> checks for new
mail, resulting in two copies of each message in the message list.
However, there are two possible side effects of this behavior, one bad
and the other worse.


If you move to a different client system you will not be able to access
your messages from the server since they have been deleted.

</Indent>

<X-Color><Param>red</Param>WARNING: </X-Color><Indent>If there is a
problem with delivering your messages to your local system it is
possible for them to be lost since the
<Fixed><Bold>popclient</Bold></Fixed> does not verify that they have
been copied correctly before deleting them the server. This is likely to
be a problem only when you are first configuring
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic>. Therefore, you might want to use the
<Bold>-k</Bold> flag (<Italic>keep messages on the server</Italic>) with
the <Fixed><Bold>popclient</Bold></Fixed> command until you are
confident that everything is working correctly.

</Indent>

§

[CARD] ishmail.prefWin.popTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] POP Server Name
Use this field to name the <Bold><Italic>POP server</Italic></Bold> from
which you will access your mail folder(s).


POP servers are typically used to serve mail folders to users connected
to the network over a slow link such as a phone line. <Italic>Internet
Access Providers</Italic> usually support IMAP and/or POP servers for
this purpose.


<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> does not have code to access a POP
server built in to the program. Instead, it uses an external command for
this purpose, which you can name in the <Bold>POP Command:</Bold> field
in this window.


§

[CARD] ishmail.pipeWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Pass Message to Filter Window
Use the <bold>Pass Message to Filter</bold> window to specify a filter or command through which you want the message to be passed. You can also specify how message headers are to be handled:


<bold><italic><bold>Filter all headers</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Filters the message and the headers that are displayed in the header window as well as all hidden headers.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Filter displayed headers only</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Filters the message and only the headers that are displayed in the header window.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Don't filter headers</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Filters the message only.


</indent>If you select multiple messages to filter, two additional options appear in the <bold>Pass Message to Filter</bold> window: <bold>Filter as separate files</bold> and <bold>Filter as one file</bold>. If you select <bold>Filter as separate files</bold>, each file is filtered individually. If you select <bold>Filter as one file</bold>, the selected files are concatenated and filtered as a single file.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Red</param>WARNING:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you choose to filter messages separately, be careful when directing standard output from the filter. If you direct standard output to a file the output from each message will write over the output from the previous message.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.buttonEditWin.orderTF.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Position
The <bold>Position</bold> field specifies the order in which you want the buttons to be displayed. The ordering is top-to-bottom if the buttons are placed in a column along the left or right edge of the window, and left-to-right if the buttons are placed in a row along the top or bottom edge of the window.


§

[CARD] ishmail.optPrefPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Preferences Option - Main, Reading, and Composition Windows
There is a <bold>Preferences</bold> option for each of <italic>Ishmail</italic>'s three main windows. 


Main Window


Choose the <bold>Application ...</bold> option to customize a number of parameters and variables in your <italic>Ishmail</italic> environment, including mail directory and file locations, print command, Web browser command, and Alert bell volume.


Reading Window


Choose the <bold>Preferences ...</bold> option to customize the format of the <bold>Reading</bold> window.


Composition Window


Choose the <bold>Window ...</bold> option to customize the format of the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


In addition to these <bold>Preference</bold> options, there are three more dialogs for customizing outgoing messages (<bold>Mail</bold>, <bold>Signature</bold>, and <bold>Reply/Forward</bold> preferences) as well as a number of other features which can be customized from the <bold>Main</bold> window <bold>Options</bold> menu.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  The decision of which parameter or variable to place into which preference window was made in a way that seemed logical to the developers of <italic>Ishmail</italic>. You may not find a preference in the window you expect. If so, keep looking. You will find it eventually.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.helpWindowPB.win.HLP
[TITLE] Primary Ishmail Windows
You read, compose and manage your mail from three primary <italic>Ishmail</italic> windows: the main window, the <bold>Reading</bold> window, and the <bold>Composition</bold> window. For detailed information about the individual windows, click the <bold>Help</bold> button, if the window has one, or select <bold>On Window</bold> from the <bold>Help</bold> menu of the window for which you want information.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you click <bold>On Window</bold> in a tear-off <bold>Help</bold> menu, you get this message. Try selecting <bold>On Window</bold> from the <bold>Help</bold> menu while it is attached to the menu bar.


</indent></indent></indentright>Even more detailed information is available from <bold>On Context</bold> help. Many parts of windows and menus have specific help cards. To see them, click <bold>On Context</bold> from the <bold>Help</bold> menu. This turns the mouse cursor into a question mark. Position the cursor over a label, field, or button in a window and click. If there is a specific help card for that part of the window, you will see it. Otherwise, the <bold>On Window</bold> help card is shown.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  The <bold>On Context</bold> help is very sensitive to cursor position. If you don't position the cursor directly over a window component, you may just see the <bold>On Window</bold> help card. Also, in some cases you may see the <bold>On Context</bold> help card if you click on a field, but not when you click on the field's label.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.printWin.printPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Print Button
Click <bold>Print</bold> to print the message(s) you specified and close the <bold>Print Message</bold> window.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If this is a non-MIME message the command used to print it is specified using the <bold>Application Preferences</bold> window from the <bold>Main</bold> window <bold>Options</bold> menu (see the <bold>Default print command</bold> field). The default is the Unix <fixed>pr</fixed> filter piped to the Unix <fixed>lp</fixed> command. 


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If this is a MIME message, the printing of the various data types contained in the message is controlled by entries in the <fixed>mailcap</fixed> file. See the <bold>mailcap</bold> entry in the help card <bold>Index</bold> for more information.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  To temporarily override the default print command for an individual message, use the <bold>Filter</bold> option rather than the <bold>Print</bold> option. This lets you explicitly specify the Unix command (or string of commands) to which the message should be sent.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.prefWin.printForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Print Command
In the <bold>Default print command</bold> field, enter the print command to use when you print messages.


You can string multiple commands together in this field using the UNIX <fixed>pipe</fixed> operation (specified by a vertical bar (|) between command names.


The default print command is <fixed>pr | lp</fixed>, which formats the message into pages, each with a running header containing time and date, before sending it to the printer.


This print command applies only to standard, ASCII messages. For MIME message components, individual print commands are specified for each data type. Some data types, for example <italic>Audio</italic>, may not have a print command. <italic>Ishmail</italic> includes print commands, <fixed>rt2ps</fixed> and <fixed>et2ps</fixed>, for MIME Rich Text and Enriched text message components. 


See the <fixed>mailcap</fixed> file in the <italic>Ishmail</italic> <fixed>lib</fixed> directory for the specification of print commands for MIME message components.


§

[CARD] ishmail.printQueryWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Print MIME Message Part
If you are printing a MIME message containing more than one part, you will see this window. It will display the type of the first (next) body part and offer four options:


<bold><italic><bold>Print this one</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Attempt to print this body part along with the rest of the message.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Skip this one</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Don't attempt to print this body part, but do not preclude printing other body parts.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Print all included and attached files</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Attempt to print all body parts, and don't ask again.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Skip all included and attached files</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Don't attempt to print any (more) body parts, and don't ask again.


</indent>MIME body parts can contain various types of data. The <fixed>mailcap</fixed> file contains entries for each data type, which specify the command to use to prepare this type of data for printing.


If there isn't a <fixed>mailcap</fixed> entry for a body part's data type, or your system doesn't support the command required for printing that data type, an error message will be printed.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  For more information on the <fixed>mailcap</fixed> file, see the <bold>mailcap</bold> entry in the help card <bold>Index</bold>.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  For more information on MIME data types, and a discussion of the difference between attached and included files, see the help cards for the <bold>Composition</bold> window.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.printWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Print Message Window
Use the <bold>Print Message</bold> window to specify that you want to print a file. You can also specify how message headers are to be handled:


<bold><italic><bold>Print all headers</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Print the message and the headers that are displayed in the header window as well as all hidden headers.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Print displayed headers only</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Print the message and only the headers that are displayed in the header window.


</indent><bold><italic><bold>Don't print headers</bold></italic></bold>

<indent>Print the message only.


</indent>If you select multiple messages to print, two additional options appear in the <bold>Print Message</bold> window: <bold>Print as separate files</bold> and <bold>Print as one file</bold>. If you select <bold>Print as separate files</bold>, each file is printed individually. If you select <bold>Print as one file</bold>, the selected files are concatenated and printed as a single file.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If this is a non-MIME message the command used to print it is specified using the <bold>Application Preferences</bold> window from the <bold>Main</bold> window <bold>Options</bold> menu (see the <bold>Default print command</bold> field). The default is the Unix <fixed>pr</fixed> filter piped to the Unix <fixed>lp</fixed> command. 


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If this is a MIME message, the printing of the various data types contained in the message is controlled by entries in the <fixed>mailcap</fixed> file. See the <bold>mailcap</bold> entry in the help card <bold>Index</bold> for more information.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  To temporarily override the default print command for an individual message, use the <bold>Filter</bold> option rather than the <bold>Print</bold> option. This lets you explicitly specify the Unix command (or string of commands) to which the message should be sent.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.msgPrintPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Print Option
Choose <Bold>Print</Bold> to send the current or selected mail message
to a designated printer. When you click <Bold>Print</Bold>,
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> displays the <Bold>Print Message</Bold> window.
From the <Bold>Print Message</Bold> window, you specify how to handle
message headers:


<Bold><Italic>Print all headers</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Print the message and the headers that are displayed in the
header window as well as all hidden headers.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Print displayed headers only</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Print the message and only the headers that are displayed in the
header window.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Don't print headers</Italic></Bold>

