[CARD] ishmail.readWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Reading Window
<Italic>Ishmail's</Italic> <Bold>Reading</Bold> window displays incoming
or saved messages. You can read ordinary mail messages or MIME messages.
MIME messages differ from ordinary messages in that they have a
structure with multiple parts, and each part can contain a different
type of multimedia data.



<Underline><Bigger><Bold>Reading MIME
Messages</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


When reading a MIME message you can view it in
<Italic>Outline</Italic> form, <Italic>Normal</Italic> form, or
<Italic>Source</Italic> form. Choose which form you want by selecting
<Bold>View</Bold> from the <Bold>Options</Bold> menu. These options have
no effect on an ordinary mail message.


In <Italic>Outline</Italic> form you can easily see the message
structure, including nesting of parts, if any. Each part is labeled with
a description of its contents. You can click on any of the parts and see
it expanded.


How a message part is expanded depends on what it contains. For example,
to look at a PostScript part you must have a PostScript viewer program
on your system, such as <Italic>ghostview</Italic>. To look at a GIF or
JPEG part you must have a viewer such as <Italic>xv</Italic> or
<Italic>display</Italic>. To listen to an audio part your system must
have audio capability and a speaker. Plain ASCII text parts and Enriched
Text parts are shown directly in the <Bold>Reading</Bold> window.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  Various viewer programs are
<Italic>not</Italic> part of <Italic>Ishmail</Italic>. If your system
doesn't have the appropriate viewer you won't be able to look at certain
attachments. However you can save them to files, for later use, or
include them in subsequent mail messages to other users.


</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>If you choose <Italic>Normal</Italic> form
to view a message all the plain text and enriched text parts are
expanded. The overall structure of the message will not be as apparent,
instead it will read like a document rather than its table of contents.


In the <Italic>Normal</Italic> view, message parts containing data other
than text will appear as icons. The icon will represent the data type,
and will be labeled with a short description of the data. Just as with
the <Italic>Outline</Italic> view, click an icon and the appropriate
view program will be launched.


To save a message part to a file, position the mouse cursor over the
icon and press and hold the right mouse button. A menu will pop up. The
menu has an option for saving the MIME attachment to a file.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  Look at the
<Bold><Italic>mailcap</Italic></Bold> file, found in the
<Bold><Italic>lib</Italic></Bold> subdirectory of where
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> is installed, to see which viewing (and
printing) programs are associated with various MIME data types. You can
modify this file to use different viewer programs.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  For simple MIME messages, containing only a single body part, you
won't see any difference between <Italic>Normal</Italic> and
<Italic>Outline</Italic> view.


</Indent></Indent>The third viewing option is <Italic>Source</Italic>.
Use this option to see the raw text of the message, without any of the
MIME structure or commands interpreted. This shows what the message
would look like if view by an e-mail tool which doesn't understand MIME.

<Indent><Indent>

</IndentRight></Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Searching for
a string</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


Press <Fixed>Ctrl-/</Fixed> to open a <Bold>Search</Bold> window. You
can specify a string of characters to search for in the current message
you are reading. There are several options:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Ignore (or honor) upper/lower case in
the search string.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Evaluate the string as a <Italic>Unix
regular expression</Italic>, or not.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Search forward or backward from the
current point in the message.


</Indent></Indent> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Printing or Filtering a
Message

</Bold></Bigger></Underline>

The contents of the message, either the message body alone or the body
and the headers, can be sent to an external command for further
processing.


The most common thing to do is send the message to a command so that it
will be printed. On the <Bold>Message</Bold> menu there is a
<Bold>Print</Bold> selection. Also, the default button setup includes a
<Bold>Print</Bold> button. When you print a message, it is sent to the
command defined in the <Bold>Application Preferences</Bold> window (from
the <Bold>Main</Bold> window <Bold>Options</Bold> menu). The default is
<Fixed>pr | lp</Fixed>, which means format the message for printing with
the <Fixed>pr</Fixed> command then send it to the <Fixed>lp</Fixed> command
to print.


If you print a MIME message containing <Italic>Rich Text</Italic> or
<Italic>Enriched Text</Italic> parts, there are special filters provided
with <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> which convert them to PostScript prior to
printing (see the <Fixed>rt2ps</Fixed> and <Fixed>et2ps</Fixed> commands
specified in the <Italic>mailcap</Italic> file).


The <Bold>Message</Bold> menu also contains a <Bold>Filter</Bold> sub-menu.
On that menu  you will see five other choices:


<Bold><<></Bold>  Convert to MIME


<Bold><<></Bold>  Decrypt


<Bold><<> </Bold> Authenticate


<Bold><<></Bold>  Edit


<Bold><<></Bold>  Other


The <Bold>Convert to MIME</Bold> option is available if you are reading
a message which was created by the Sun <Italic>mailtool</Italic> program.
The mailtool can generate multi-media messages, but they don't follow
the MIME specification. <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> contains a special
filter which can convert these messages to MIME format.


The <Bold>Decrypt</Bold> and <Bold>Authenticate</Bold> options are used
with mail which has been encrypted or signed with a digital signature.
See the help card for the <Bold>Reading Window Preferences</Bold> menu
for more details about the decryption and authentication commands.


<X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color>
<Indent><Italic>Ishmail</Italic> does
<X-Color><Param>red</Param>not</X-Color> contain any encryption
technology. You must supply external commands for this purpose. U.S.
laws restrict the export of encryption technology.

</Indent>

The <Bold>Edit</Bold> option lets you edit a message in the folder. The
existing message will be marked for deletion and a new message,
containing your changes, is added to the folder. This is useful in the
following scenario, for example: Someone sends you a message containing
some text and a very large binary attachment, such as a video clip. You
want to save the message text, but you don't want the video clip taking
up a lot of space in your mail folder. You could forward the message to
yourself and edit out the video clip, but now the message will appear to
have come from you rather than the original sender. With the
<Bold>Edit</Bold> option, you can remove the video clip without
otherwise changing the message headers.


<X-Color><Param>yellow</Param>CAUTION:</X-Color> A<Indent>fter editing a
message, you must save changes to the folder to cause your edits to be
saved permanently in the folder. Otherwise you edits will be lost when
you close the folder.

</Indent>

The <Bold>Other</Bold> option on the <Bold>Filter</Bold> menu lets you
send (<Italic>pipe</Italic>, in Unix terminology) the message to a
command. This is the general case of all the preceding
<Bold>Filter</Bold> and <Bold>Print</Bold> options. 


When you click <Bold>Other</Bold> <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> displays the
<Bold>Pass Message to Filter</Bold> window. In the <Bold>Pass Message to
Filter</Bold> window, enter the name of the filter command through which
you want the message passed. This can be a sequence of commands, such
as<Fixed>pr | lp</Fixed>. 


<X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP:</X-Color> <Indent>You can specify a
full path name if the command is not in your search path. Also, you can
use shell environment variables, such as<Fixed> $HOME</Fixed>. The
string that you enter will be sent to your login shell for processing.

</Indent>

You can also specify how message headers are to be handled:


<Bold><Italic>Filter all headers</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Filters the message and the headers that are displayed in the
header window as well as all hidden headers.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Filter displayed headers only</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Filters the message and only the headers that are displayed in
the header window.


</Indent><Bold><Italic>Don't filter headers</Italic></Bold>

<Indent>Filters the message only.

</Indent>

<Underline><Bigger><Bold>

</Bold></Bigger></Underline> <Underline><Bigger><Bold>Resizing Reading
Windows

</Bold></Bigger></Underline>

You can resize a <Bold>Reading</Bold> window using the window manager's
resizing features. As you resize the window vertically, the message body
area grows or shrinks proportionally while the header fields remain the
same size. As you resize the window horizontally, both areas grow or
shrink proportionally.


Vertical and horizontal scroll bars provide the ability to scroll the
text within the message viewing area.


There is also a <Bold>Wrap text</Bold> button on the
<Bold>Options</Bold> menu. If you click this button <Fixed>On</Fixed> lines
of text will wrap at the right margin, and you will not need a
horizontal scroll bar.


<X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP:<Indent> </X-Color>To make the setting
of the Wrap text button permanent, use the Reading Window Preferences
window.


</Indent>

<Underline><Bigger><Bold>Pinning a Reading
Window</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


By default, <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> automatically replaces the text of
a reading window with the text of the next message you want to read. To
review multiple messages at the same time, "pin" the reading windows
that contain messages for which you do not want the text replaced.



<Underline><Bigger><Bold>Setting up Shortcut
Buttons</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


You can configure shortcut buttons to help streamline your use of the
<Bold>Reading</Bold> window. There are numerous possible functions in
the <Bold>Reading</Bold> window menus that can be mapped to buttons, in
addition to the one supplied by default. To set up buttons, use the
<Bold>Buttons</Bold> option in the <Bold>Options</Bold> menu of the
<Bold>Reading</Bold> window.



<Underline><Bigger><Bold>Getting More
Information</Bold></Bigger></Underline>


To get more information about <Italic>Ishmail</Italic> components:


<Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Move the pointer onto the component.
If <Bold>QuickHelp</Bold> is available for the component, a terse
description of the component appears in the message area near the bottom
of the window.


</Indent><Bold><<></Bold><Indent>   Select <Bold>On Context</Bold> from
the <Bold>Help</Bold> menu. The pointer changes into a question mark.
Move the question mark onto the component, and click.
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> displays a <Bold>Help Card</Bold> containing
concise information about the component and how to use it within the
application.


</Indent></Indent>§

