[CARD] ishmail.readPrefWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Reading Window Preferences
Use the <Bold>Reading Window Preferences</Bold> window to control the
size of the Reading Window, to control format of MIME messages, and to
control text wrapping behavior.


You can set the number of rows to be used for displaying headers from
the message, as well as number of rows to be used for displaying the
message itself.


You can set the number of columns which are shown in the Reading window.
If the text in the window needs more columns than are available, scroll
bars are placed on the text area border. Or, if you have enable the
<Bold>Wrap text at right margin</Bold> option, Ishmail will reformat the
text to fit the window.


Another way to change the size of the window is to click on the outside
window border and drag horizontally or vertically. Changes made this way
do not stay in effect the next time you run <Italic>Ishmail</Italic>.


Other preferences you can set include:

<Bold>

<<></Bold> Control <Indent>whether structured (MIME) messages are shown
in outline form, flattened (expanded) form, or in raw source
form.</Indent>


<Bold><<></Bold> Specify <Indent>the command to be used for viewing a
URL (<Italic>Universal Resource Locator</Italic>, i.e. a World Wide Web
address). URLs are highlighted in the <Bold>Reading</Bold> window. Place
the cursor over the URL and press the CTRL key while clicking the mouse
to cause the external viewer to be launched.

</Indent>

<Indent><X-Color><Param>Green</Param>TIP:</X-Color><Indent> The default
command exploits a feature of the
<Fixed><Bold>netscape</Bold></Fixed> browser which lets you send it a
new URL to view without launching another copy of the program. Leaving a
copy of <Fixed><Bold>netscape</Bold></Fixed> running and using this
feature greatly reduces the delay between clicking the URL and seeing
the Web page.

</Indent>

<X-Color><Param>Yellow</Param>CAUTION:</X-Color> <Indent>The default
command uses the <Bold>-install</Bold> flag with
<Fixed><Bold>netscape</Bold></Fixed>. This causes netscape to take over
the color map when it is running, so that it can best show true color
images. A side effect is the the colors of other programs look very
strange while the <Fixed><Bold>netscape</Bold></Fixed> window is in
focus. Do not worry, this is not a problem.

</Indent>

</Indent><Bold><<></Bold> Specify <Indent>commands for decrypting
messages and authenticating digital signatures.


<X-Color><Param>blue</Param>NOTE:</X-Color> <Indent>The
<Bold><Italic>Ishmail</Italic></Bold> package
<X-Color><Param>red</Param>does not</X-Color> include any encryption
commands. You must supply these yourself. U.S. laws strictly regulate
export of encryption technology.

</Indent></Indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.readPrefWin.viewFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reading Window View Type for MIME Messages
When reading a MIME message you can view it in
<Italic><Bold>Outline</Bold></Italic> form,
<Italic><Bold>Flat</Bold></Italic> form, or
<Italic><Bold>Source</Bold></Italic> form. Chose which form you want by
clicking one of the <Bold>View type:</Bold> radio buttons. These buttons
have no effect on an ordinary mail message.


You can set the default type here, or override the default on a per
message basis by clicking the <Bold>View type:</Bold> radio buttons in
the <Bold>Reading</Bold> window.


In <Italic><Bold>Outline</Bold></Italic> form you can easily see the
message structure, including nesting of parts, if any. Each part is
labeled with a description of its contents. You can click on any of the
parts and see it expanded.


If you choose <Italic><Bold>Flat</Bold></Italic> form to view a message
all the plain text and enriched text parts are expanded, or
<Italic>flattened</Italic>. The overall structure of the message will
not be as apparent, instead it will read like a document rather than its
table of contents.


In the <Italic><Bold>Flat</Bold></Italic> view, message parts containing
data other than text will appear as icons. The icon will represent the
data type, and will be labeled with a short description of the data.
Just as with the <Bold><Italic>Outline</Italic></Bold> view, click an
icon and the appropriate view program will be launched.


If you choose <Bold><Italic>Source</Italic></Bold> form, you will see
the raw text of the message. No attempt is made to interpret MIME
structure nor apply imbedded MIME formatting commands.


§

[CARD] ishmail.prefWin.recentForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Remember the Most Recent Folders
<italic>Ishmail</italic> keeps a list of the most recently used folders, and presents this list when you select the <bold>Save to Folder (Recent)</bold> option. This gives you a quick way to pick folders without having to type their name or use the <bold>Folder Selection</bold> dialog.


The default value is <fixed>10</fixed>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.editPlainPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Remove Formatting Attributes
Select <bold>Plain</bold> to remove any formatting applied to the selected text, such as:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   boldface


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   italic


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   underlined


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   bigger or smaller point size


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   indentation


</indent></indent>All the format changes that have been applied to the selected text are removed. For example, if you have made the selected text bold, italic, and underlined and you then use <bold>Plain</bold>, all three attributes are reset. If you wanted to keep one or two of them, you would have to reapply them.


§

[CARD] ishmail.readWin.replyCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Menu Option
The <bold>Reply</bold> pull-down menu provides options for replying to the current message and for forwarding the current message.


For more information on various options use Help on Context for that option.


§

[CARD] ishmail.msgReplyCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Option
Use the <bold>Reply</bold> option to perform operations on selected mail messages. 


Choose among six options in the <bold>Reply</bold> menu to <bold>Reply</bold> to messages, <bold>Forward</bold> messages or <bold>Resend</bold> them:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Reply to sender only


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Reply to sender only and include the original message


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Reply to all recipients of the message


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Reply to all recipients of the message and include the original message


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Forward


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Forward encapsulated


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Resend


</indent></indent>When you reply to a message, you send mail back to the sender of the message. 


When you forward a message, you pass it on to someone else, possibly with some additions or changes. 


When you forward an encapsulated message, the original message appears as an attachment to a new message you compose. 


When you resend a message, it appears to the new recipient as if the message came from the original sender rather than from you.


When you have selected one of these options, <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Composition</bold> window appears. The <bold>Composition</bold> window contains a subject field, recipient fields, and a composition field in which to enter your message.


§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.attribForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Attribution string
This field specifies an attribution string to use in message responses. 


The default string is <<$from:wrote:>, where <<$from:> is the associated line from the mail header command through which messages are filtered.


Any keyword found in the message header can be referred to as a variable by preceding its name with a dollar sign "$" and following it with a "<fixed>:</fixed>" (colon), for example <<$to>:, <<$subject>:, <<$in-reply-to>:. If the specified header is not found in a particular mail message the variable name is used as a literal. In other words, if the preference defines the attribution string as <<$xyz said:> and an <<xyz:> line is not found in the message header, the attribution string will literally be <<$xyz said:>.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Refer to <italic><underline>RFC822</underline></italic> for a list of standard keywords. If you wish to define new keywords, follow the guidelines in <italic><underline>RFC822</underline></italic>.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.begForwardForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Begin forwarded message string
This field specifies the string to include at the beginning of forwarded messages. Any valid text string can be used. 


The default string is:


>>>>>Forwarded message from $from:


§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.endForwardForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - End forwarded message string
This field specifies the string to include at the end of forwarded messages. Any valid text string can be used. 


The default string is:


<<<<<<<<<<End forwarded message


§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.forwardHeadFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Forwarded headers option
In the <bold>Displayed Headers Option</bold> dialog you can specify which mail headers should be shown in the <bold>Reading</bold> window. When you forward a message, by clicking one of the <bold>Forward these headers:</bold> radio buttons you can specify whether the forwarded message should contain:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   All the headers from the original message


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Only the headers displayed in the <bold>Reading</bold> window


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   No mail headers


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.indentForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Indent lines in responses string
This field specifies the prefix to use for each line in the original message of a reply. Any valid text string can be used. 


The default character is a greater-than symbol (<fixed>></fixed>).


§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.numberTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Numbering Replies
When you reply to a message <italic>Ishmail</italic>, as well as various other mail tools, changes the original subject line by adding the prefix <italic>Re:</italic>. For example, when reply to mail with the subject <italic>Question about Ishmail</italic> the subject in the reply will become <italic>Re: Question about Ishmail</italic>. If the reply is replied to, the subject becomes <italic>Re: Re: Question about Ishmail</italic>.


Toggle this parameter <fixed>On</fixed> to cause <italic>Ishmail</italic> to condense all <italic>Re:</italic> prefixes into a single prefix, that is numbered to indicate how many times replies have been traded on this subject. For example, the <italic>Re: Re: Question about Ishmail</italic> subject in the previous example would become instead <italic>Re[2]: Question about Ishmail</italic>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.stripTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Remove comment text from addresses
E-mail addresses can be adorned with various information which is ignored by the mail transport subsystem, but which make the address more readable to humans. In Ishmail, this extra information is referred to as <italic>comment text</italic>. Given the address <fixed>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net</fixed>, here are two examples containing comment text:


<fixed><bold>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net (Ishmail Technical Support)</bold></fixed>


<fixed><bold>Ishmail Technical Support <<ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net></bold></fixed>


In order to avoid cluttering the <bold>To:</bold> field in the <bold>Composition</bold> window, Ishmail strips off any comment text from addresses. You can override this behavior by toggling this parameter <fixed>On</fixed>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.replyPrefWin.removeMeTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Reply Preferences - Remove me from recipient list in replies
Toggle this parameter <fixed>On</fixed> to have your name removed from the recipient list when replying to a message that has your name in the <bold>To:</bold> field or the <bold>Cc:</bold> field. This preference helps ensure that you don't get a copy of your own reply.


Redundant replies can occur if you are listed in either the <bold><italic>To:</italic></bold> or <bold><italic>Cc:</italic></bold> fields of an incoming message. 


In some cases, however, you may still generate an additional reply copy. This could happen if your alias gets expanded to a full Internet address. In that case, the pattern matching routine that removes your alias from the recipient list will not be able to find a match for the full address.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  In some cases, when you set this option, you may still generate an additional reply copy. This could happen if your alias gets expanded to a full Internet address. Then, the pattern matching routine that removes your alias from the recipient list will not be able to find a match for the full address. 


</indent></indent></indentright>§

