[CARD] ishmail.optReplyPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Replying to and Forwarding Mail Option
Choose the <bold>Reply/Forward ...</bold> option to customize formatting of mail your reply to or forward.


Things that can be customized include:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Whether or not to remove your address automatically from replies


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Whether or not to number a sequence of replies, for example: <fixed>Re:</fixed>, <fixed>Re[2]:</fixed>, <fixed>Re[3]:</fixed>, etc.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Whether to indent excerpted text in a reply, and what characters to use to mark the excerpt


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   What string to use to attribute an excerpt in a reply


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Strings to use to delimit a forwarded message


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Which headers to include in forwarded mail


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.msgResendPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Resend Option
Choose <bold>Resend</bold> to resend the current or selected message to one or more recipients.


The are two similar options, <bold>Forward</bold> and <bold>Resend</bold>. When you <italic>forward</italic> a message you have the opportunity to edit its contents before passing it on. The recipients will see a return address for the message as if you composed and sent it. When you <italic>resend</italic> a message you cannot edit its contents before passing it on, and it will appear to recipients as if it came from the original sender rather than from you. (Note that a mail header is added indicating that the message was resent, and by whom.)


When you click <bold>Resend</bold>, <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Composition</bold> window. The <bold>Composition</bold> window contains a recipient field, subject field, and <bold>Message</bold> area. Note that the <bold>Message</bold> area is grayed-out, indicating that it cannot be selected or edited.


§

[CARD] ishmail.fileSavePB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Mail Template
Select this option to create a file containing the contents of the <bold>Composition</bold> window. A file selection dialog will be opened, letting you choose a file name. Use this option to create a template for future mail messages, based on the message you are currently composing.


§

[CARD] ishmail.msgSaveCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Message Option
Choose <bold>Save</bold> to save the current or selected messages to the folder of file you specify. To specify where to save the message(s), you choose one of three sub-options: <bold>To default folder</bold>, <bold>To folder</bold>, or <bold>To file</bold>.


If the <bold><italic>Delete messages after saving</italic></bold> preference is set, the message will be marked as deleted in addition to being marked as saved. 


If the <bold>Hide deleted messages</bold> is set, the message will be removed from the message list.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  To change the name of the default save file or to change the current settings of the <bold>Delete messages after saving</bold> or the <bold>Hide deleted messages</bold> option, use the <bold>Preferences</bold> option of the <bold>Options</bold> menu.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.savePartWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Save Message Part Window
Use the <bold>Save Message Part</bold> window to select a file name into which you will save part of the message you are reading. The part of the message to be saved is the selected (highlighted) part.


If you know the name of the file you wish to use, enter the name in the <bold>Selected File</bold> field and click <bold><italic>OK</italic></bold> (or press <fixed>Ctrl-Return</fixed> or <fixed>Ctrl-Enter</fixed>).


You can use wild card characters in the file name. Wild cards will be expanded using the shell specified by your <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> environment variable, or by your login shell if <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> is not set. If the wild card pattern returns multiple names, only the first file name will be used.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> recognizes two wild card characters in addition to those handled by the shell. If the first character of a file name is a plus (<fixed>+</fixed>) or an equal sign (<fixed>=</fixed>), it is replaced by the name of your folder directory (typically, <bold><italic>$HOME/Mail</italic></bold>).


If you select the name of an existing file, <italic>Ishmail</italic> asks if you want to overwrite the file or cancel and select a different name.


To see the names of existing files and directories, click the <bold>Show list</bold> button to the right of the <bold>Selected Folders</bold> field. <italic>Ishmail</italic> opens a file list. You can use this expanded file selection window to navigate within your system's directory structure. 


To close the this window without saving to a file, click <bold>Cancel</bold>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.saveFileWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Save Message to File Window
Use the <bold>Save Message to File</bold> window to select a file name into which you will save the message(s) you have selected.


If you know the name of the file you wish to use, enter the name in the <bold>Selected File</bold> field and click <bold><italic>OK</italic></bold> (or press <fixed>Ctrl-Return</fixed> or <fixed>Ctrl-Enter</fixed>).


You can use wild card characters in the file name. Wild cards will be expanded using the shell specified by your <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> environment variable, or by <bold><italic>/bin/sh</italic></bold> if <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> is not set. If the wild card pattern returns multiple names, only the first name will be used.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> recognizes two wild card characters in addition to those handled by the shell. If the first character of a file name is a plus (<fixed>+</fixed>) or an equal sign (<fixed>=</fixed>), it is replaced by the name of your folder directory (typically, <bold><italic>$HOME/Mail</italic></bold>).


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can use a command, or sequence of commands, in this field if you enclose them with back-quote (`) characters. For example, to include all files in the current directory and its subdirectories, do the following:


</indent></indent></indentright><fixed><bold>`find . -type f -print`</bold></fixed>


To see the names of existing files and directories, click the <bold>Show list</bold> button to the right of the <bold>Selected Folders</bold> field. <italic>Ishmail</italic> opens a file list. You can use this expanded file selection window to navigate within your system's directory structure. 


To close this window without including or attaching a file, click <bold>Cancel</bold>.


§

[CARD] ishmail.msgSaveRecentCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Message, Pick From Recent Folders Option
This option provides a quick way to access folder names. Choose <bold>To Folder (Recent)</bold> to save the current or selected messages to a name you pick from a list of folder names. Slide the mouse cursor to the right to see a list of the most recently used folder names. See the <bold>Application Preferences</bold> option to change how many names are kept in the list. The default is 10.


§

[CARD] ishmail.saveRuleWin.removePB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Pattern - Delete Button
Highlight a save pattern and click <bold>Delete</bold> to remove it from the <bold>Save Pattern List</bold>. <italic>Ishmail</italic> asks you to confirm your action before it deletes the save pattern.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can remove more than one save pattern at a time by highlighting multiple icons.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.saveRuleWin.modifyPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Pattern - Edit Button
Highlight an icon and click <bold>Edit</bold> to begin editing a save pattern. <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Edit Save Pattern</bold> window. Then:


<indent>1.	<indent>Make your changes in the <bold>Pattern</bold> and <bold>File name</bold> fields. 


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Click <bold>Apply</bold> or <bold>OK</bold> in the <bold>Edit Save Pattern</bold> window to apply your changes to the selected save pattern.


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.saveRuleWin.insertPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Pattern - Insert Button
Highlight an icon and click <bold>Insert</bold> to begin inserting a new save pattern. <italic>Ishmail</italic> displays the <bold>Edit Save Pattern</bold> window. Then:


<indent>1.	<indent>Place the pointer in the <bold>Pattern</bold>: text field and enter a string pattern that should appear in the header field of an incoming message.


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Place the pointer in the <bold>Folder name</bold> text field and enter the name of the folder that should be used when the string pattern is encountered in a message header.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Folder names can be fully qualified path names or relative path names. Relative path names are resolved starting from your <fixed>$HOME</fixed> directory. Relative path names starting with a <fixed>+</fixed> or an <fixed>=</fixed> are resolved starting from your <bold><italic>Folder Directory</italic></bold>, which is typically <fixed>$HOME/Mail</fixed>.


</indent></indent></indentright></indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>Click <bold>OK</bold> or <bold>Apply</bold> in the <bold>Edit Save Pattern</bold> dialog window.


</indent></indent>§

[CARD] ishmail.saveRuleWin.addPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Pattern - New Button
To create a new save pattern:


<indent>1.	<indent>Click the <bold>New ...</bold> button. The <bold>Edit Save Pattern</bold> window appears.


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Place the pointer in the <bold>Pattern</bold>: text field and enter a string pattern that would appear in the header field of an incoming message.


