[CARD] ishmail.optSavePB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save Patterns Option
Choose the <bold>Saving</bold> option to specify patterns which influence which folders are used when mail messages are saved to the <italic>default</italic> folder.


You specify patterns (following the <italic>regular expression</italic> syntax of the Unix <fixed>ed</fixed> command) and associated folder names. When saving a message, the patterns are searched for in the headers. If a match is found, the associated folder name is used to save the message - if the <bold>Save by Pattern</bold> option is enabled. See the <bold>Preferences - Application</bold> help card for more details.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  This option differs from the <bold>Automatic Filing</bold> option. Though both look for matching patterns in mail headers to decide into which folder a message should be saved, the <bold>Automatic Filing</bold> option does this automatically for new mail arriving in the <bold>InBox</bold> folder, while the <bold>Save Patterns</bold> option is invoked when you select one or more messages to move from one folder to another


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.saveRuleWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Save Patterns Window
The <bold><italic>Save Patterns ...</italic></bold> option lets you define patterns which influence which folder is selected when you save a message.


When you save a message you can explicitly choose a folder in which to put the message, or save to the default folder. The default folder can be a single folder (the same one each time you save) or it can change depending upon the contents of the message's headers. The <bold><italic>Application Preferences ...</italic></bold> option lets you choose how the default folder is determined. One of your choices is to pick the folder name based upon matching a pattern in the message's headers. The <bold>Save Patterns</bold> option lets you define the patterns and their associated folder names.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  This option differs from the <bold>Automatic Filing</bold> option. Though both look for matching patterns in mail headers to decide into which folder a message should be saved, the <bold>Automatic Filing</bold> option does this automatically for new mail arriving in the <bold>InBox</bold> folder, while the <bold>Save Patterns</bold> option is invoked when you select one or more messages to move from one folder to another


</indent></indent></indentright>You specify a string pattern and a folder name. When you save a mail message to the default folder (and the <bold><italic>Save According to Pattern</italic></bold> option is enabled) the headers are scanned for a match with the patterns. When a match is detected the message is saved into the associated folder.


The <bold><italic>Save Patterns</italic></bold> window shows the list of current string patterns and associated folder names in a box containing two text fields --- the <bold>Pattern</bold> name field and the associated <bold>Folder name</bold> field. (If no save patterns have been defined, both fields are empty.) 


The pattern is evaluated as a <italic>regular expression</italic>, as defined by the UNIX <fixed>ed</fixed> command.


You use the four buttons to the left of the text fields to:


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Create a new save pattern.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Insert a save pattern.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Edit an existing save pattern.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   Remove an existing save pattern.


</indent></indent>When you click the <bold>New ..., Insert ...</bold>, or <bold>Edit ...</bold> buttons, the <bold><italic>Edit Save Pattern</italic></bold> window appears. It contains text fields in which you can create or modify a save pattern.


§

