[CARD] ishmail.msgSaveQuickCB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Save to Folder, Pick From List Option
This option provides a quick way to access folder names. Choose <bold>To Folder (List)</bold> to save the current or selected messages to a name you pick from a list of folder names. Slide the mouse cursor to the right to see a list of all the folder names in your folder directory (typically <fixed>$HOME/Mail</fixed>). See the <bold>Application Preferences</bold> option to specify your folder directory.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Red</param>WARNING:</x-color></bold><indent>  If you have many folders in you folder directory, there will be a pause (up to several seconds) as the list of names is built. This "quick access" option may not be very quick if you have a large number of folders.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Green</param>TIP:</x-color></bold><indent>  You can <italic>tear off</italic> the folder name list by clicking the dotted line at the top of the menu. This leaves the list displayed even after you click a name in the list.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.saveSelectWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Save to Selected Message(s) to Folder Window
Use the <bold>Save to Selected Folder</bold> window to select a mail folder into which you will save one or more messages.


If you know the name of the folder you wish to open, enter the name in the <bold>Selected Folders</bold> field and click <fixed>OK</fixed> (or press <fixed>Ctrl-Return</fixed> or <fixed>Ctrl-Enter</fixed>).


You can use wild card characters in the file name. Wild cards will be expanded using the shell specified by your <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> environment variable, or by <bold><italic>/bin/sh</italic></bold> if <bold><italic>$SHELL</italic></bold> is not set. If the wild card pattern returns multiple names, the only first name will be used.


<italic>Ishmail</italic> recognizes two wild card characters in addition to those handled by the shell. If the first character of a file name is a plus (<fixed>+</fixed>) or an equal sign (<fixed>=</fixed>), it is replaced by the name of your folder directory (typically, <bold><italic>$HOME/Mail</italic></bold>).


Ishmail can handle folders in either <bold><italic>mail</italic></bold> or <bold><italic>mh</italic></bold> format. In the <bold><italic>mail</italic></bold> format (also used by <bold><italic>mailx</italic></bold>, <bold><italic>elm</italic></bold>, etc.) a folder is a file containing one or more messages. In the <bold><italic>mh</italic></bold> format (also used by <bold><italic>xmh</italic></bold> and <bold><italic>exmh</italic></bold>) a folder is a directory and each message is an individual file in a directory.


If you use a name which does not correspond to an existing folder <italic>Ishmail</italic> asks if you want to create the folder. You will be given the option of creating a standard Unix-style folder or and MH-style folder.


Click on <bold><italic>Show List</italic></bold> to show an expanded window which contains additional fields. Using these additional fields you can navigate in your file system to find and select folders. Use <bold>help on context</bold> to see more information about each.


To close the this window without selecting a folder, click <bold>Cancel</bold>.


