§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.win.HLP
[TITLE] Sort Specification Window
Use the <bold>Sort Specification</bold> window to specify the order in which mail messages are displayed in the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area of the main window.


<indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   You can specify sort order using up to eight available sort keys. 


<indent>1.	<indent>Subject thread


</indent></indent><indent>2.	<indent>Message number


</indent></indent><indent>3.	<indent>Message status


</indent></indent><indent>4.	<indent>Subject


</indent></indent><indent>5.	<indent>Sender


</indent></indent><indent>6.	<indent>Date


</indent></indent><indent>7.	<indent>Number of lines


</indent></indent><indent>8.	<indent>Number of bytes


</indent></indent></indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   For each sort key, you can specify the direction of the sort, either ascending or descending.


</indent></indent><indent><bold><<></bold><indent>   You can specify a different sort key for each folder.


</indent></indent>The <bold>Sort Specification</bold> window contains a row of toggle buttons, each of which controls an associated sort key. Adjacent to each sort key is a pair of radio buttons for controlling sort direction---either ascending or descending. (For alphabetical characters, ascending order is A to Z; descending order is Z to A.) The radio buttons for the <bold>Status</bold> key act differently, in that they select between the sort orders <bold>New</bold>, <bold>Unread</bold>, and <bold>Other</bold> and <bold>Other</bold>, <bold>Unread</bold>, and <bold>New</bold>. The <bold>Selected keys</bold> box below the <bold>Available sort keys</bold> area shows the results of your sort criteria selections. 


When you toggle <fixed>On</fixed> a button that corresponds to a sort key, a number appears in the <bold>Order</bold> column to the left of the buttons. The number indicates the precedence of the sort key. The first key you toggle <fixed>On</fixed> becomes key <fixed>1</fixed>, the second becomes key <fixed>2</fixed>, and so on. Conversely, if you toggle that button <fixed>Off</fixed>, the corresponding sort key is removed and the number is removed from the <bold>Order</bold> column. The other sort keys are renumbered. You can specify any or all eight sort keys and any order of direction in your sort specification.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.bytesFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Byte Count Option
Select <bold>Byte Count</bold> to sort mail messages by number of bytes, or characters. If you display mail messages by byte count in ascending order, the messages with the lowest byte count appear at the top of the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area.


Only the characters in the message body are counted, not the characters in the headers.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  Some mail messages contain a <fixed>Content-Length:</fixed> header. This is a good indication of the number of bytes in a message, but it is not always accurate. <italic>Ishmail</italic> counts the number of bytes instead of relying on a <fixed>Content-Length:</fixed> header, if present.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.dateFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Date Option
Select <bold>Date</bold> to sort mail messages by the time and date the message was sent, as indicated by the message's <fixed>Date:</fixed> header. If you display mail messages by date in ascending order, the oldest messages appear at the top of the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  This differs from sorting by <bold>Number</bold> in that <bold>Number</bold> indicates the order in which messages were received, while <bold>Date</bold> indicates when a message was sent. These usually result in the same sort order, but not necessarily. Differences result from variable delays in the mail network and differences in clock time among systems.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.linesFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Line Count Option
Select <bold>Line Count</bold> to sort mail messages by line count. If you display mail messages by line count in ascending order, the shortest messages appear at the top of the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area.


A <italic>line</italic> is counted as a string of characters ending with a <fixed>newline</fixed> character.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  For messages containing data other than ASCII text, for example GIF or JPEG data, the count of number of lines may not be meaningful.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.numberFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Message Number Option
Select the <bold>Number</bold> option to sort mail messages by number. When you do this, the first mail messages to arrive have the lower number. So, if you sort in descending numerical order, the newest messages appear at the top of the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area. If you sort in ascending numerical order, the oldest messages appear at the top of the <bold>Folder Contents</bold> area.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  This differs from sorting by <bold>Date</bold> in that <bold>Number</bold> indicates the order in which messages were received, while <bold>Date</bold> indicates when a message was sent. These usually result in the same sort order, but not necessarily. Differences result from variable delays in the mail network and differences in clock time among systems.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.statusFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Message Status Option
Select <bold>Status</bold> to sort mail messages by status. The buttons for the <bold>Status</bold> key select between the two sort orders <bold>New, Unread, Other</bold> and <bold>Other, Unread, New</bold>. 


§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.senderFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Sender Option
Select <bold>Sender</bold> to sort mail messages in alpha-numerically by sender's name, as found in the message's <fixed>From:</fixed> header. For alphabetical characters, ascending order is A to Z; descending order is Z to A.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.subjectFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Subject Option
Select <bold>Subject</bold> to sort mail messages alpha-numerically by subject, as indicated by the message's <fixed>Subject:</fixed> header. For alphabetical characters, ascending order is A to Z; descending order is Z to A.


§

[CARD] ishmail.sortWin.threadFrame.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sort by Subject Thread Option
Select the Thread option to sort mail messages by subject thread. When you do this, messages will be grouped in the message list according to their subject line (from the <fixed>Subject:</fixed> mail header). If you sort in ascending order, the oldest subject in you folder is shown first.


To illustrate how this works, consider this example: You have 3 messages in your folder, each with a different subject line. Applying <bold>Sort By Thread</bold> has no apparent, immediate effect. The messages remain sorted by arrival sequence. When new mail with a unique subject arrives it is added to the end of the list, so the list still appears sorted by number. However, when new mail arrives containing a subject line which matches an existing message, the new message appears inserted in the list just after the message with the same subject.


§

[CARD] ishmail.prefWin.alertTB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Sound Alert Toggle Button
Toggle the <bold>Sound Alert</bold> button <fixed>On</fixed> to have <italic>Ishmail</italic> sound a "beep" or execute an <bold>Alert</bold> command executed each time new mail arrives. 


The default value for this parameter is <fixed>On</fixed>.


For more information about <bold>Alert</bold> commands, see the help card for the <bold>Alerts</bold> option on the main window <bold>Options</bold> menu.


§

[CARD] ishmail.fileSpellPB.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Spelling Checker Option
You can use an external spelling checker command to verify the spelling of your message. The default command used is <italic>ispell</italic>. You can change the default spelling checker command in the <bold>Composition Window Preferences</bold> dialog.


<indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Blue</param>NOTE:</x-color></bold><indent>  If your message contains MIME <italic>Enriched Text</italic>, for example italic, bold, or underlined text, then <italic>mark-up tags</italic> are inserted into the text. These don't appear in the <bold>Composition</bold> window (instead, you see the effect of the format change) but <italic>do</italic> appear in the text sent to the spell checker command. The <italic>ispell</italic> command will flag most of these as spelling errors. You can ignore these errors.


</indent></indent></indentright><indent><indentright><bold><x-color><param>Yellow</param>CAUTION:</x-color></bold><indent> If you have set the <bold>Message type</bold> to <fixed>Plain</fixed>, enriched text mark-up tags are stripped from the file before it is sent to the spelling checker. You won't see lots of spurious spelling errors, but you will lose the formatting changes after the spelling checker completes.


</indent></indent></indentright>§

[CARD] ishmail.mainWindow.statusform.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Status Message
The status message displays information about the actions taken on messages. For example, when you update your in-box folder, the status message is "In-box updated".


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.subjectForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] Subject Field
In the <bold><italic>Subject</italic></bold> field, enter a brief description that identifies the message to be sent. 


The <bold><italic>Subject</italic></bold> field scrolls horizontally, as you enter text, to accommodate lengthy entries. You can use the arrow keys to reveal existing text that is beyond the margins.


Press Return or Tab to move the pointer to the next field. 


§

[CARD] ishmail.sendWin.toForm.ctx.HLP
[TITLE] To Field
Click the pointer in the <Bold><Italic>To</Italic></Bold> field and
enter the e-mail addresses and aliases for all primary recipients of the
message. Separate individual addresses and aliases with a comma (,) or
press<Fixed> Return/Enter</Fixed> to place addresses on separate lines.


<Indent><IndentRight><X-Color><Param>green</Param><Bold>TIP:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  You can separate addresses with a single space only, and
<Italic>Ishmail</Italic> automatically inserts the comma, if you enable
the <Italic>Allow spaces to delimit addresses</Italic> feature in the
<Bold>Composition Window Preferences</Bold> window.


</Indent><X-Color><Param>blue</Param><Bold>NOTE:</Bold></X-Color><Indent>  You can use addresses which contain comment information, such as the
recipient's real name. For example: <Fixed>Tech Support
<<ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net></Fixed> or <Fixed>ishmail-support@lists.sourceforge.net (Tech
Support)</Fixed>.

</IndentRight></Indent></Indent>

The <Bold><Italic>To</Italic></Bold> field scrolls horizontally, as you
enter text, to accommodate lengthy entries. You can use the arrow keys
to reveal existing text that is beyond the margins.


A vertical scroll bar is added as necessary if you place addresses on
separate lines.


<X-Color><Param>green</Param>TIP: </X-Color><Indent>Click the
<Bold>[...]</Bold> button at the upper right of the field to see a list
of e-mail aliases.

</Indent>

Press <Fixed>Tab</Fixed> to move the pointer to the next field. 


